<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kyrgyzstan President Names Acting Prime Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Kyrgyzstan President Askar
Akayevich Akayev has appointed Kubanychbek Zhumaliyev, director of
the presidential office, as acting prime minister to replace Apas
Jumagulov.
</P>
<P>
Jumagulov, who became prime minister in December 1993,
presented his resignation to President Akayev on Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
Zhumaliyev, 42, a doctor of applied sciences, is a former first
deputy educational minister and chairman of the presidential
science and technology committee.
</P>
<P>
Jumagulov stepped down saying he was too old for the post, and
added that reforms in the Central Asian state would demand someone
with stronger stamina.
</P>
<P>
The president may name the new prime minister on Wednesday when
he is expected to address parliament.
</P>
<P>
According to Kyrgyzstan's constitution, the president appoints
the prime minister with the consent of the parliament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
