<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zhu Rongji Outlines Cross-Century Tasks Facing State Council (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 24 (Xinhua) -- At the first plenary meeting of
the new State Council, Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji today urged
State Council members to treasure power entrusted by the people
and perform their duties in line with the Chinese Constitution.
</P>
<P>
Zhu outlined the major cross-century tasks of the State
Council, and stressed the need for further emancipating the mind,
seeking truth from facts, deepening reforms and expanding opening
in order to promote the great cause of building socialism with
Chinese characteristics as the 21st century approaches.
</P>
<P>
The members approved the Plan for the Establishment of
Operational Units of the State Council and Restructuring
Coordinating Bodies, as well as the revised Working Regulations of
the State Council.
</P>
<P>
Zhu said that the State Council will solve a number of social
and economic problems over the next five years. The future is
bright and full of hope, he added.
</P>
<P>
Zhu said the proper management over the next five years will
raise China's reform and development efforts to a new level.
</P>
<P>
He praised the achievements of the previous government led by
former premier Li Peng, and noted that progress resulting
therefrom has established a solid foundation for the future work
of the State Council.
</P>
<P>
Zhu said China's material and technological base has been greatly
enhanced, with the nation's foreign exchange reserves and grain
storage reaching record highs.
</P>
<P>
"More importantly, we have a complete set of theories, guiding
lines, principles and policies which have been proved to be correct
in practice," said Zhu.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the Central Committee of the Chinese Communist
Party with Jiang Zemin at the core is full capable of managing
various difficult situations.
</P>
<P>
"We have braved various domestic and international challenges
and tests over the past years, and we will undoubtedly win victories
in the face of new challenges and tests," said Zhu.
</P>
<P>
He added that 1998 will be a key year for his government to
achieve various objectives.
</P>
<P>
Zhu said the government will strive to ensure an eight-percent
national economic growth rate, keep inflation at below three
percent and maintain a stable exchange rate for the Renminbi.
</P>
<P>
He also called for stimulating domestic demands and giving full
play to the vast potential of the domestic market.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980325.0009 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zhu Rongji Outlines Cross-Century Tasks Facing State Council (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China plans to increase investments in fixed assets, with
priority placed on inputs to agriculture, forestry and water
conservancy projects, as well as infrastructure construction in
the railway, highway, telecommunications and environmental
protection sectors, and new and high-tech programs.
</P>
<P>
Zhu called for accelerated housing reform and construction to
established a new growth point in economic development.
</P>
<P>
He said China will continue to promote agricultural development
and enhance poverty relief efforts, with an additional 10 million
rural residents expected to shake off poverty in 1998.
</P>
<P>
On restructuring China's economy and government institutions,
Zhu said that the reforms of State-owned enterprises, the
financial system and government bodies are vital to the overall
situation in the country.
</P>
<P>
He said the CPC Central Committee has set goals for the reforms
and the State Council must achieve them within the next three
years.
</P>
<P>
The system of appointing supervising commissioners for
State-owned enterprises will be established, Zhu said, adding it
will be an important measure to separate government functions from
enterprise management.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out the need to make greater efforts to restructure
the financial system and noted that the order in the financial
sector must be rectified with a focus on strengthening the
regulatory and supervisory role of the Central Bank and
accelerating the independent operation of commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
Zhu also addressed reforms of the grain circulation
sector, and the investment, housing, medical care, social security
services and taxation systems. He noted that reform efforts should
be well coordinated and managed in line with China's economic and
social development.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980325.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zhu Rongji Outlines Cross-Century Tasks Facing State Council (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Zhu said the State Council also plans to place priority on
reemployment projects so as to ensure the basic subsistence
requirements of laid-off workers.
</P>
<P>
Governments at all levels should provide professional training
courses and introduce correct employment concepts in order to
create more job opportunities, while encouraging laid-off workers
to employ them by themselves, Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
The premier noted that great importance will be placed on
restructuring government institutions and realizing the separation
of government functions from enterprises management, instead of
simply shifting power from one government department to another.
</P>
<P>
He noted that ministries and commissions under the State
Council will be streamlined and the number of public servants
reduced. Zhu added that restructuring programs should be
properly arranged to prevent negative impacts on the normal work
of the government.
</P>
<P>
The premier urged departments concerned to improve training
programs to sharpen the competitiveness of public servants.
</P>
<P>
Zhu stressed that the staff of the State Council should be
fully cognizant of their position as public servants and should
work whole-heartedly for the people, adhere to the truth even at
the expense of personal interests, and devote themselves to the
battle against corruption and the establishment of a clean and
honest government.
</P>
<P>
Participants agreed with Zhu's call for future work
inspection tours to strictly adhere to the principle of frugality
and scheduling work conferences in sites other that resort areas.
</P>
<P>
Senior officials with the State Council will attend major
activities organized by the Central Committee of the Communist
Party of China and the State Council, but will refrain from
attending various other events such as ribbon-cutting and awards
ceremonies in order to concentrate fully on study of major issues.
</P>
<P>
Vice-premiers Li Lanqing, Qian Qichen, Wu Bangguo and Wen
Jiabao attended today's meeting along with State councillors Chi
Haotian, Luo Gan, Wu Yi, Ismail Amat and Wang Zhongyu. 
</P>
</TEXT>
