<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Karachi Stocks Slide Due to Renewed Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, March 24 (Xinhua) -- The Karachi shares index went
down slightly Tuesday amidst increased violence in the Pakistan's
biggest city which has left 20 dead.
</P>
<P>
Fighting between members of the Mutahida Qaumi Movement (MQM)
and its splinter group, the MQM (Haqiqi), has also made the main
shopping and commercial areas of the city remain closed on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Stocks market analysts say that trading volumes were also down
Tuesday as the city was not fully functional and the main
commercial areas were shut.
</P>
<P>
The 100-Index of Karachi Stock Exchange (KSE) ended down 2.07
points to close at 1512.25 with a trading volume of 43.4 million
shares as compared to Friday's close of 1514.32 on 54 million
shares.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts were hopeful that the market would pick up in the
week as reaction to the city's violence was not as drastic as
market expectations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
