<DOCNO> XIE19980325.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-24 16:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli President: Compromise on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Israeli President Ezer Weizman
on Tuesday expressed his confidence that a compromise can be
reached over the scope of Israeli troop pullback in the West Bank
between the concerned parties.
</P>
<P>
After a meeting with the United Nations Secretary General Kofi
Annan, Weizman told reporters there are proposals that Israel
withdraw from 9 or 13 percent of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
All the parties concerned, the Israelis and the Palestinians in
particular, will reach a compromise in this regard, he added.
</P>
<P>
The United States has reportedly outlined an initiative that
Israel should pull back its troops from 13.1 percent of the West
Bank in several phases over 12 weeks.
</P>
<P>
But Israel has said the withdrawal scope is "unacceptable" and
"damaging Israel's security interests" and asked the U.S. not to
go public with it. The Jewish state insists that it will withdraw
from no more than 9 percent of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli president voiced his concern about the situation in
the Middle East and asked the U.N. chief to exercise his personal
influence to prevent it from exploding.
</P>
<P>
"The (U.N.) secretary general has made great contributions in
helping solve the Iraq crisis and so he can do his best in
preventing the situation here from exploding," Weizman said.
</P>
<P>
Annan reached an agreement on U.N. weapons inspections with
Iraq a month ago after tough and successful mediation, which
averted a possible military attack on Iraq by the U.S..
</P>
<P>
After the meeting with Weizman, Annan told reporters that the
Mideast peace process is facing trouble and all parties concerned
should make efforts to put it back on track.
</P>
<P>
"During my tour of this region, everyone that I have met has
spoken about the strategic decisions to achieve peace, which will
help move the peace process forward," he said.
</P>
<P>
Annan arrived here on Tuesday on the last leg of his regional
trip, which has taken him to Jordan, Egypt, Lebanon, Syria and the
Palestinian self-rule area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
