<DOCNO> XIE19980325.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Harvard Scholars Seek Deeper Understanding of China (1) (by Li Xiguang and Chen Jie) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 24 (Xinhua) -- "I am at the beginning of a
voyage of discovery -- one I have looked forward to for many
years," said Harvard President Neil Rudenstine, who is visiting
China.
</P>
<P>
Rudenstine made the comments during an address to 800-odd
Beijing University teachers and students Monday.
</P>
<P>
"In fact, it was in 1877 that Mr. Francis Knight -- an American
who had been living for years in China -- returned to his home in
Boston for an extended visit. He suggested -- and Harvard agreed
-- that our University should hire its first teacher of Mandarin
Chinese. Mr. Knight returned to China and engaged the services of
Mr. Ko Kun-hua of Ningpo, who came, very bravely, to the
wilderness of Harvard in 1879 -- with his wife and six small
children -- to begin instruction in the elegant intricacies of
your venerable language."
</P>
<P>
Some 100-odd years have passed and Rudenstine and his wife are
currently visiting China. "I come to you in the spirit of
friendship and learning," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Although this is the first visit to China for my wife and me,
I have seen a lot and learned a lot. I cannot wait to anticipate
another trip to China," said Rudenstine, who arrived in Beijing
on Saturday and will depart for southern China on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"The United States and China are different in culture and
tradition, and have a lot to learn from each other," said
Rudenstine, a scholar of Renaissance literature. "I have visited
the Forbidden City and the Temple of Heaven, and I feel very
excited."
</P>
<P>
Rudenstine is the first sitting president of Harvard to visit
China, a fact which indicates that the university, a highly
prestigious Western academic institution which directly influences
the attitudes major U.S. sectors hold concerning China, is in the
process of expanding its recognition of the country.
</P>
<P>
"Early in this century, when scholars at Harvard first began to
study China in a serious way, questions were raised about whether
the University was using its resources wisely," according to
Rudenstine.
</P>
<P>
"Now at the end of this century, in our increasingly
interconnected world, it is impossible to imagine how China could
not be a significant focus of study at American universities. It
is hard to imagine anyone questioning the importance and
even 'usefulness' of studying China."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980325.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Harvard Scholars Seek Deeper Understanding of China (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
He pointed out that one of Harvard's most significant research
projects is an ongoing collaborative effort focused on the
"complicated interplay between economic development, energy use
and environmental protection." The project involves more than 100
scholars from both China and the United States.
</P>
<P>
Rudenstine said Chinese scholars working with the Harvard law
faculty a number of years ago helped the university establish the
first Chinese law program in the United States.
</P>
<P>
"This shows how strongly we are committed to a wider
understanding of China, and to a broader dialogue with colleagues
in China on other matters of common interest.
</P>
<P>
"How can we manage rapid changes in the global economy? How do
we prevent the spread of terrible infectious diseases? Given the
major changes in the international landscape in recent years, how
can we build a framework for a durable peace in the future? These
and many other questions can be intelligently addressed only if we
strengthen our capacity to work together across traditional
academic borders, and across traditional national and regional
boundaries.
</P>
<P>
"All of us will need to consider how to incorporate and
accommodate a greater diversity of people, and a greater variety
of attitudes, customs, and ideas. We will have to learn how to
sustain our own deepest cultural and human values, while also
living more closely with -- and learning from -- others who have
different values," said Rudenstine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
