<DOCNO> XIE19980325.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Harvard Scholars Seek Deeper Understanding of China (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Several thousand scholars in the United States are engaged in
Sinocology, including influential scholars Ezra Vogel and William
Kirby who are visiting China along with Rudenstine.
</P>
<P>
Vogel, director of the Fairbank Center for East Asian Research
and director of the Harvard University Asia Center, speaks fluent
Chinese. His published works include "Japan as Number One: Lessons
for America," "One Step Ahead in China: Guangdong Under Reform"
and "Four Little Dragons."
</P>
<P>
Vogel, who refers to himself as "a student of Japan and China
for 40 years," told Xinhua that "it is as comfortable as at home
to be in China."
</P>
<P>
He noted that Fairbank was unable to get used to the changes
and was "somewhat uncomfortable" during his 1972 visit to China.
</P>
<P>
"In the 21st century, the most important force will be in
Asia. China has the most rapid economic growth rate in the world,"
said Vogel, who hosted Chinese President Jiang Zemin during a
visit to Harvard in November 1997.
</P>
<P>
He noted that "Living With China," which he recently edited,
provides an avenue for all sectors in the United States to reach a
consensus and live with China.
</P>
<P>
"The 21st century will face many problems. The US and China
should learn from each other and understand each other. The US
should open up more to China, and American scholars should inform
the American people of China's progress," said Vogel.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that interest groups and the bias of the
U.S. media have deprived the American public of access to detailed
information concerning changes which have taken place and are
still taking place in China, including the emergence of private
enterprises and government efforts to decontrol prices.
</P>
<P>
William Kirby, a senior faculty member with Harvard's Asia
Center and the Fairbank Center for East Asia Research, has worked
as a Visiting Professor at both Beijing University and Nanjing
University.
</P>
<P>
He noted that China has a great and continuous
civilization. "Every time I come to China, the change is so fast,
and I don't think you can see any part of the world that is moving
so fast. That's very exciting."
</P>
<P>
Kirby, who initiated his studies of China during the Vietnam
War Era, said that one of his research projects focuses on
"watching the change of China."
</P>
<P>
Kirby is currently working on three books related to China --
"The International Development of China," "China and the World in
the 20th Century" and "A World Transformed: A Global History of
the 20th Century."
</P>
<P>
"I think there's great promise for China," said Kirby. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980325.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Economy Is Resilient, says minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's Finance Minister Herbert
Murerwa Tuesday said the country's economy is resilient and will
survive the current difficulties.
</P>
<P>
The minsiter siad that the market is poised for better
prices of some exports with flue-cured tobacco prices expected to be
fairly bouyant this year.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a meeting of heads of Christian denominations,
Murerwa said there were already signs of
recovery, with the strengthening of the Zimbabwean Ddollar from about
18 Zimbabwean Dollars in January to 16.5 against one U.S. Dollar in March
this year.
</P>
<P>
''Horticultural exports are also doing very well and have
therefore contributed to the firming of the Zimbabwean dollar,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
He also predicted that the agricultural sector would experience a modest grow
th,
which should bring about stability in prices of food, in addition to
the foreign exchange earning from exports, the Zimbabwe News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Murerwa said the economy was estimated to have grown by 3.7
percent in 1997, a weak performance compared to 1996 when the economy
grew by 7.2 percent in real terms.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the weak performance to lower production by the
agricultural and mining sectors which declined by two percent and six
percent respectively in real terms during 1997.
</P>
<P>
''The decline in agricultural activities was due to excessive
rains which reduced production volumes of the major agricultural
crops. Maize production declined by 15.9 percent, cotton by 7.5
percent and tobacco by 7.1 percent,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
''The mining sector suffered heavily from depressed international
prices of our major minerals such as gold, nickel and chrome,''
he added.
</P>
<P>
But the manufacturing sector was estimated to have experienced an
impressive growth of 8.5 percent in real terms.
</P>
<P>
To resolve the balance of payments problem, the minister said the
government was currently involved in discussions with the IMF on a
stand-by agreement with a view to increasing foreign currency
reserves and ensuring stability of the Zimbabwean Dollar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980325.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African, Russian Diamond Giants Set Up Joint </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 24 (Xinhua) -- De Beers, South African
diamond giant, has concluded a 50-50 joint-venture agreement with
Russia's Soglasiye gem miner to exploit the rich Lomonosov
deposit near Arkhangelsk, northwest Russia, a De Beers official
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The venture will be the first to allow a foreign company to
mine diamonds on Russian soil, said Raymond Clarke, the Head of
De Beers in Moscow, the capital of Russia.
</P>
<P>
De Beers, the world's largest diamond producer, said the the
latest Russian government shake-up by President Boris Yeltsin
should have no immediate effect on the company's gem sales
agreement with Russia.
</P>
<P>
De Beers signed an agreement last October, which expires at
the end of this year. Under the agreement, Russia will sell at
least 550 million U.S. Dollars in rough Russian gems a year to De
Beers.
</P>
<P>
Officials at De Beers and Almazy Rossi-Sakha, the Russian
diamond monopoly, expect the total to exceed the minimum.
</P>
</TEXT>
