<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nissan Announces New Era in Vehicle Communications </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 24 (Xinhua) - Nissan's US carmaker Infiniti is
launching an in-car satellite system that automatically calls for
help in an accident, tracks down car thieves and even eavesdrops
on their conversation.
</P>
<P>
According to an announcement by the company here Tuesday, the
"Infiniti Communicator" can also be sued for touch-of-a-button
breakdown and medical assistance and will remotely open car doors
in the event of a lock-out.
</P>
<P>
The system features two buttons and a microphone located in a
console above the driving seat. It uses Global Positioning System
(GPS) and cellular phone technology linked up to a 24 hour
Infiniti Response Center (IRC).
</P>
<P>
If a collision sets off an air-bag then the Infiniti
Communicator automatically alerts the response center. The
operator attempts voice contact, calls the emergency services and
identifies the vehicle's exact position with a GPS readout.
</P>
<P>
In an emergency the driver can summon the breakdown or
emergency services at the touch of a button. One button identified
with the picture of an ambulance is for high priority situations
such as an accident or medical emergency.
</P>
<P>
The other button marked with a circle "I" for information is
for lower priority calls such as roadside assistance or general
travel information. The IRC operator can identify the vehicle's
position and summon the relevant service, even if voice contract
is not possible.
</P>
<P>
If the vehicle's security system is triggered by a thief the
Infiniti Communicator automatically calls the response center. The
operator immediately notifies the local police and calls the
owner's emergency number.
</P>
<P>
The response center provides the police with tracking
information if the vehicle is stolen. Staff inform the police of
vehicle location, direction, speed, licence number, colour and
vehicle identification number. When the ignition is on, the police
can monitor the thief's conversation.
</P>
<P>
In the event of a lock-out, owners can request remote door
unlocking immediately or at a specified time by calling a free
phone number and providing a personal password.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980325.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Museum Receives Precious Manuscript of Mathematician </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 24 (Xinhua) -- The widow of the late Chinese
mathematician Chen Jingrun donated Chen's manuscript of the
thesis, the Proof for "Goldbach's Conjecture 1 + 2," to the Museum
of the Chinese Revolution today.
</P>
<P>
The manuscript was about Chen's work on Goldbach's conjecture,
which proved that "each large even number can be expressed as the
sum of a prime and an integer that is the product of at most two
primes."
</P>
<P>
A national science magazine published the digest of the
manuscript in 1966. Chen advanced the proof in 1973, and a theorem
has been named after him.
</P>
<P>
The manuscript was found in the Mathematics Institute of the
Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS) last year, where Chen, a former
academician of CAS, had been working.
</P>
<P>
"The manuscript is one of the most precious cultural relics the
museum has collected these years," said Dong Baohua, deputy
director of the State Bureau of Cultural Relics, adding that it
will soon be put on show in a large exhibition about the
development of modern China, sponsored by the museum. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
