<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Announces New Interest Rate Reduction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 24 (Xinhua) -- The People's Bank of China
(PBOC), the nation's central bank, has announced that the interest
rates on bank loans and deposits will be lowered effective
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The central bank has also decided to begin reform of the
deposit reserve fund system on March 21, and will reduce interest
rates on loans and deposits granted to financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
Interest rates for deposits and loans will be reduced by an
average 0.16 and 0.6 percentage points respectively.
</P>
<P>
Benchmark interest rates for one-year deposits will drop from
5.67 percent to 5.22 percent, with the rate for two-year deposits
falling from 5.94 percent to 5.58 percent.
</P>
<P>
Interest rates on demand deposits, as well as three-month,
six-month, three-year and five-year term deposits, will remain
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Six-month lending rates will be lowered from 7.65 percent to
7.02 percent, with reductions also set for longer term lending
rates.
</P>
<P>
The latest round of interest rate reductions, which follows
reductions in October last year, is in response to sharply
declining prices.
</P>
<P>
Interest payment burdens on borrowers, especially state-owned
enterprises, will be eased somewhat since interest rates for loans
will fall more than rates for deposits.
</P>
<P>
From the standpoint of reform of the deposit reserve fund
system, the central bank will combine two existing reserve fund
accounts, and will reduce the legal ratio of deposit reserve funds
from 13 percent to eight percent.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the central bank has decided to lower annual
interest rate on the deposits of financial institutions from 7.35
percent to 5.22 percent. And, annual interest rates on loans to
financial institutions will fall from 9.19 percent to 7.43
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980325.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK PM Denies Helping Murdoch Win Mediaset Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 24 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
on Tuesday denied reports he had approached Italian Prime Minister
Romano Prodi in an attempt to help the News Corp boss Rupert
Murdoch break into Italian television.
</P>
<P>
The reports said Blair secretly contacted Prodi last week to
support Murdoch's bid to gain control of Mediaset,the media
company controlled by Silvio Berlusconi, Italy's former prime
minister.
</P>
<P>
Blair's official spokesman told a regular briefing the claims
Blair had helped Murdoch in the business were "a complete joke".
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said Prodi's conversation through phone calls
with Blair was part of their regular contact during Britain's
presidency of the European Union.
</P>
<P>
"This was not a conversation about Rupert Murdoch," he added.
</P>
<P>
Talks on the television deal collapsed last Friday after
Berlusconi rejected a 5.8 trillion lire (3.2 billion U.S. dollars)
offer to buy his stake. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
