<HEADLINE> Zambia Reaffirms Support for Angolan Peace Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Zambian president's special envoy
Erick Silwamba said here on Tuesday that the Zamban government
will continue to observe the U.N. resolutions on sanctions
against Angola's former rebel National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA) and support the full
implementation of the 1994 Lusaka Peace Accord.
</P>
<P>
Silwamba made the remarks after he passed a letter from
President Frederick Chiluba on to Angolan President Eduardo Dos
Santos.
</P>
<P>
The Zambian government will exert its effort to help fully
implement the UN Security Council's resolutions on sanctions
against UNITA and the Lusaka Peace Accord until peace is achieved
in Angola, said Silwamba.
</P>
<P>
President Dos Santos said that the Angolan government will
firmly regard peace as its highest goal and promote the full
implementation of the Lusaka Peace Accord.
</P>
<P>
Recently, there has been some skirmishes in the relations
between Angola and Zambia. The Angolan government criticized
Zambia for damaging the peace process by providing support
for UNITA, violating the UN resolutions.
</P>
<P>
Now, the two countried are working to improve the bilateral
relations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
