<DOCNO> XIE19980325.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ireland to Hold Referendum on Amsterdam Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 24 (Xinhua) -- The Republic of Ireland will hold
a national referendum on the Amsterdam Treaty -- the new European
Union Treaty -- in May, according to press reports from Dublin
early Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
An Irish government spokeswoman said that the referendum, on
whether to forge closer relationship with the 15-nation bloc, will
be held on May 22.
</P>
<P>
The Amsterdam Treaty, which replaced the Maastricht Treaty of
1992 to become the new EU Treaty, aims to enhance cooperation on
crime, health, unemployment, consumer protection and the
environment within the EU.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that the Irish referendum was designed as a
safety measure to avoid any potential legal challenges to the
Treaty in the future.
</P>
<P>
However, the result of the national referendum is likely to be
a strong "yes" vote as a European Commission survey last November
revealed that more than 80 percent of Irish voters supported the
country's EU membership. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980325.0044 </DOCNO>
