<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Exports to See Another Robust Growth in 1998, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Germany's export boom is set to
continue with an expected growth of 11.5 percent in 1998 after a
remarkable 10.5 percent rise registered last year, the German
Wholesale and Foreign Trade Association BGA said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to BGA president Michael Fuchs, Germany's exports are
expected to climb to 989 billion marks (540 billion U.S. dollars)
in 1998 from the 1997 level of 887 billion marks (490 billion
dollars).
</P>
<P>
The BGA estimate is much more optimistic than that of the
German government which put the 1998 German export growth at just
7.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to the BGA, Germany's imports would also expand by
nine percent to 834 billion marks (460 billion dollars) this year
from the 1997 reading of 766 billion marks (420 billion dollars).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
