<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Open to U.S. Initiative, Says Egyptian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) President Yasser Arafat is keen to discuss the new
U.S. proposal to revive the Mideast peace process, Egyptian
Presidential Advisor Osama el-Baz said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
During talks with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak here
Tuesday, Arafat expounded his vision regarding the current
U.S. initiative as well as his readiness to meet with U.S. Mideast
Peace Envoy Dennis Ross on Thursday, Baz told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"Arafat expressed keenness to discuss everything to be proposed
in this connection," he said.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to advance the stalled Israeli-Palestinian peace
talks, the U.S. has called on Israel to carry out a 13.1 percent
second withdrawal in the West Bank linked to the fulfillment of
Palestinian commitments to fight terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Both Palestinians and Israelis have expressed reservations over
the plan. Israel said it can afford to pull out from no more than
10 percent of the territories while the PNA demands at least 20
percent.
</P>
<P>
In an attempt to persuade Israel and the Palestinians to accept
the new initiative, Ross will visit the region this week.
</P>
<P>
Arafat also wants to maintain impetus of a mediation drive by
foreign powers concerned especially the U.S. and Europe in the
Mideast peace process, Baz added.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that Washington will maintain its
interest in the peace march and offer proposals that could be
accepted especially by the Palestinian side.
</P>
<P>
Baz described the Palestinians as the party which has been so
far adversely affected by the stalemate in the peace-making.
</P>
<P>
He said any U.S. initiative should take into consideration the
basic demands and requirements of the Palestinians and not just be
a "mere refection of the Israeli point of view."
</P>
<P>
Arafat, who arrived here early in the day on a few hours' visit
to Egypt, had talks with Mubarak and addressed the opening session
of the 109th Arab League Council meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
