<DOCNO> XIE19980325.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WFP to Airlift Food for Children in Burundi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 24 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations World Food
Program (WFP) will start on Wednesday an airlift of food for
37,000 malnourished children in nutritional centers throughout
Burundi.
</P>
<P>
In a press release issued here on Tuesday, WFP said that a
Boeing 707 would deliver 34 tons of powdered milk on Wednesday
morning to Bujumbura airport.
</P>
<P>
In the next 10 days, WFP will airlift to Burundi a total of
600 tons of sugar, powdered milk, oil and other relief supplies
which will be used in 111 feeding centers in the central African
country.
</P>
<P>
Jean Siblot, WFP's Country Director for Burundi, was quoted as
saying "malnutrition in this country is on the rise and some
300,000 people are facing major food shortages."
</P>
<P>
As a result, the press release said, WFP has given priority to
nutritional feeding programs for 37,000 children in centers run
by non-governmental organizations.
</P>
<P>
WFP has to resort to an urgent airlift of food as the El
Nino-induced heavy rains and flooding destroyed the roads and
rail networks from Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of the year, only 1,500 tons of food have
been delivered to Burundi every month against the required 5,000
tons monthly need for some 300,000 people.
</P>
<P>
Siblot noted that "our stocks of food aid in Burundi have hit
rock bottom" and "we are only receiving a fraction of what we
need."
</P>
<P>
The WFP airlift has been approved by the Regional Sanctions
Coordinating Committee as shipments of humanitarian supplies into
Burundi require clearance from national and regional sanctions
committees.
</P>
<P>
Economic sanctions against Burundi were imposed by countries
in east and central Africa in July 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980325.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Drug Users Need Help for Treatment: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 24 (Xinhua) -- A paucity of treatment for young
drug users in Britain led to a seven-year gap between the age they
started taking drugs and when they tried to get treatment for
their addiction, says a survey Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The survey, carried out among some 500 drug users aged 14-59
found that addicts started to take drugs at 15 on average,
recognized they had a problem at 17, but did not seek help until
they were 22.
</P>
<P>
The survey attributed the gap to a lack of treatment for young
drug users for whom there are only a handful of specialist
detoxification centers.
</P>
<P>
Peter Martin, chief executive of the drugs agency Addaction,
which carried out the survey, called on the UK government to
address the problem in its new strategy on drug prevention.
</P>
<P>
"Young people are getting to a point of crisis. There's a
paucity of services. The whole policy area needs to be thought
through," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Department of Health said that it was aware of "a problem
with the number of services for young people" and it would spend 37
million pounds (61 million US dollars) on drug treatment this
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980325.0051 </DOCNO>
