<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania to Go Ahead with Controversial Prawns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 24 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzanian government
will go ahead with the controversial Rufiji Delta Prawns Project
and has maintained that its endorsement by the cabinet last
November was irreversible, Daily News said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Minister for Natural Resources and Tourism, Zakia Meghji,
reiterated Monday that local and international experts will
closely monitor the environmental impact of the multi-million U.S
Dollars project.
</P>
<P>
"Two commissions have been formed to monitor the development
of the project to ensure that there is no environmental
destruction of the the project site," Meghji told reporters in
Dar es Salaam.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the project has six sites, the sixth of
which is the largest covering about 6,000 of a total of 10,000
hectares, and that it will not adversely affect the environs
since it is out of the mangroves program area on the delta.
</P>
<P>
Environmentalists have expressed fears that the project will
destroy a large tract of mangrove trees along the coast. In
addition, they claimed that pollution, coastal deforestation,
soil erosion, the collapse of fisheries and social conflicts over
land are some of the common consequences of commercial
aquiculture.
</P>
<P>
In response, Meghji said the investor of the proposed project,
Messrs African Fishing Company, has already been notified of the
government's conditions to ensure there will be no destruction of
the environment.
</P>
<P>
The company intends to cultivate over 20,000 hectares of land
on the delta for development of ponds for prawns farming.
</P>
<P>
The minister also assured that the investors are going to
engage in extensive farming instead of intensive farming of the
prawns. "Extensive farming is one of the conditions we have
agreed upon since it is widely known that intensive farming of
prawns required a lot of compounds which normally lead to rampant
prawn diseases," Meghji said.
</P>
<P>
Meghji also insisted that the investors will be prohibited to
use destructive chemicals in the project.
</P>
<P>
The company has yet to embark on the project and the
government is still waiting for its program of action for
evaluation, she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980325.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-24 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Cypriot Leader Rules Out Bicommunal Dialog </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf
Denktash has ruled out talks with his rival Greek Cypriot
community counterpart, saying no U.N. resolution would make him
return to the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
Denktash's comments came only a few days after top U.N. envoy
for Cyprus Diego Cordovez announced that he would seek guidance
from the Security Council on demands by Denktash to change the
basis of the negotiations to "state-to-state" talks instead of an
intercommunal dialog.
</P>
<P>
Cordovez was in Cyprus last week for meetings with President
Glafcos Clerides and Denktash, in a bid to break the deadlock and
revive the peace process on the island.
</P>
<P>
Denktash told the Turkish Cypriot newspaper Kibris, published
Tuesday in Turkish Cypriot-controlled northern part of Nicosia,
that he would outline his views to U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan at a meeting in Geneva on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Annan-Denktash meeting was confirmed Tuesday by Acting
U.N. spokesman Juan Carlos Brandt in New York. During the meeting,
the Turkish Cypriot leader is expected to raise his demand to
change the status of the interlocutors in Cyprus peace talks,
demanding for recognition of his breakaway Republic in northern
Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Denktash was quoted by the paper as saying that he did not
believe the Security Council would modify its attitude toward the
Turkish Cypriots and adopt a resolution in their favour.
</P>
<P>
"We have made it clear that we are ending the talks. Why should
we talk, since the (EU) accession process (with the Cypriot
government) is continuing? If they insist too much we shall bring
back to the foreground integration with Turkey," Denktash said.
</P>
<P>
Denktash has hardened his stance on Cyprus issue following the
European Union (EU)'s decision to start accession talks with the
Cypriot government on March 31.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus problem has remained unresolved since 1974 when the
island was divided after Turkish troops invaded and took over the
northern third in the wake of a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots declared a breakaway "Turkish Republic of
Northern Cyprus" in November 1983, only recognized by
Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
