<DOCNO> XIE19980325.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> TB Emerges as Public Health Threat: WHO Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Tuberculosis (EB), which has been
considered a disease of the past, emerged again as a major public
health threat and has been declared a global emergency, a World
Health Organisation (WHO) official said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing participants at a meeting marking the World TB Day
in Harare, WHO regional representative in Zimbabwe, Levon
Arevshatian said, ''It is estimated that TB kills some three
million people per year, representing more than five percent
deaths globally,'' the Zimbabwe News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
He said although TB largely affected poor people, it was also
growing in industrialised countries.
</P>
<P>
''It is now recognised that there is a strong relationship
between TB and HIV infection. HIV damages the immune system and
TB progresses to a life-threatening disease,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
Arevshatian encouraged TB sufferers not to stop their
treatment once it started. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
