<HEADLINE> EU Plans Action against French Organizers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 24 (Xinhua) -- The European Union Commission
Tuesday planned action against the French organizers of the 1998
World Cup for rejecting demands to sell all remaining tickets
outside France.
</P>
<P>
Karel Van Miert, commissioner in charge of market competition,
said the commission had to take a last-minute decision on sending
France a letter of warning prior to taking the action it was
planning.
</P>
<P>
A fine of up to 10 percent of the turnover from what the
commissioner described as wrongly-sole tickets was among a couple
of measures the commission was planning.
</P>
<P>
But Van Miert said that it was impossible now to calculate the
number of the wrongly-sold tickets.
</P>
<P>
The commissioner also did not rule out the possiblity of taking
the French organizers to the European court of justice in that he
argued selling the remaining tickets to French residents only was
a discrimination running against the Article 86 of the EU
cmpetition law.
</P>
<P>
The French organizers have so far received 2 million ticket
request for the 64 games to be played during this year's grand
finale in France.
</P>
<P>
Of the remaining 160,000 tickets, 50,000 have been promised to
the football associations of the European Union nations whereas
the remainder will be sold to French supporters, according to the
organizers' planning.
</P>
<P>
The EU has demanded to sell the remaining tickets on a
first-come-first-serve basis and yet the French organizers did not
heed the demand.
</P>
<P>
Van Miert said that the commission had been promised a final
reply by the French organizers for mid-last week but did not get
any word until late Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
"The French did not even make a sporting gesture by allowing
non-resident supporters to have enve a phone call chance,"said Van
Miert, "It would be fair for others to have some chance at least."
</P>
<P>
The commissioner said that the EU would have respected the
organizers' rules shoule they have accepted the EU proposal and
redressed the issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
