<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> London Overtakes Tokyo in Stock Stakes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 24 (Xinhua) -- London's stock market has leapt
past Tokyo in valuation terms to become the second largest stock
market in the world, according to figures from FTSE
International's world valuation table Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the London stock market, which was just a
six of the Tokyo market's size nine years ago when the Japan
market was at its peak, is now worth 1,930 billion US dollars,
1.50 percent higher than Japanese stocks, worth 1,900 billion US
dollars.
</P>
<P>
American stock market, the largest in the world, are now worth
9,077 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
It said that the movement followed the deepening of the
financial crisis in Japan, and the international community fears
that Japan is not doing enough to rescue its economy.
</P>
<P>
But it added that British stocks have been flattered by the
recent rise in sterling and the yen's weakness although the
cross-rate, at 218 yen to the pound, is slightly weaker than the
1989 rate of 231 yen.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
