<BODY>
<HEADLINE> F-16 Crashes in Utah </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 24 (Xinhua) -- An F-16 aircraft crashed onto
a runway during an attempted landing at a military base in Utah
Monday, but the pilot ejected safely.
</P>
<P>
There was a small fire after the crash at the Hill Air Force
Base, about 120 kilometers west of Salt Lake City, but the extent
of the damage to the plane was unknown, said the Associated Press
in a report Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The pilot, Lt. Col. John Burgess, was treated at the base
hospital for minor injuries Monday night.
</P>
<P>
The pilot radioed ahead to air traffic control warning of
mechanical problems when the plane was returning from the Utah
Test and Training Range.
</P>
<P>
Since F-16s arrived at Hill nearly two decades ago, 40 have
crashed, including two in January. F-16s cost up to 20 million
U.S. dollars each. 
</P>
</TEXT>
