<HEADLINE> S. African Trade Mission to Tour China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 24 (Xinhua) -- A government and business
delegation led by Trade and Industry Minister Alec Erwin will
leave for China at the weekend for a week-long trade and
investment tour, South Africa Press Association (SAPA) reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The trip is aimed at selling South Africa and the Southern
African Development Community (SADC) and attracting investment in
the region, ministry spokesman Themba Rubushe said.
</P>
<P>
The focus would be on sectors such as agro-processing,
chemicals, mining and machinery, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Although the PRC (People's Republic of China) is more
developed than South Africa, there are sectors where South Africa
believes it has an upper hand in mining technology, the banking
industry and energy," Rubushe was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The delegation would also discuss the possibility of
establishing a trade and economic joint committee and expect to
sign an agreement on trade, economic and technical cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of diplomatic relations with China on
January 1 opened doors for South Africa to enter the Chinese
market, Rubushe said.
</P>
<P>
He said China's economy was growing at eight percent per year.
Its import was growing by 10 percent and its export by five
percent per year. 
