<HEADLINE> Junta Remnants Fight Back in East S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Remnants of the dislodged military
junta in Sierra Leone and rebel allies have fought back in the
east of the country two weeks after the comeback of the
legitimate government.
</P>
<P>
The fleeing forces took over three towns by Monday, defeating
the pro-government civil defense group known as Kamajors there,
the British Broadcasting Corporation reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Scores of people, including women and children, were killed by
the junta forces, the report said, quoted people fleeing from
that area.
</P>
<P>
A Kamajor commander confirmed that they were repelled from the
area after running out of ammunition during the four days of
battle with the junta forces.
</P>
<P>
He also attributed the Kamajors' failure to lack of food and
logistics, adding that they were now regrouping for another
offensive.
</P>
<P>
The junta, which seized power in a coup last May, was driven
out of the capital Freetown in mid-February by the west African
peace keeping force ECOMOG.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian-led sub-regional force has vowed to clean up the
remnants of the junta forces and the rebel Revolutionary United
Front. But lack of international assistance has affected its
operations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
