<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-24 19:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Stresses Implementation of U.N. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 24 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary General Kofi
Annan said here Tuesday that he will work with Israel and all the
parties concerned to ensure the U.N. Resolution 425 will be
implemented effectively.
</P>
<P>
After his meeting with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu, Annan told a joint press conference with Netanyahu that
all Security Council resolutions, including Resolution 425 which
calls on Israel to withdraw from South Lebanon, must be
implemented.
</P>
<P>
Annan said that the only way this region must go is to advance
the peace process, adding that he will do whatever he can to
assist pushing this process forward.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said that Israel is willing to pull back its troops
from South Lebanon, noting that the Israeli Cabinet will continue
discussions on the issue and make a formal decision.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli government is currently studying the plan put
forward by Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai, under which Israel
would withdraw from South Lebanon after getting security
guarantees from Beirut.
</P>
<P>
Annan said that the discussions on the issue will take some
time, but it is the step in the right direction.
</P>
<P>
When asked if the Lebanese government is capable of making
independent decisions without Syria, Annan said that there is an
effective Lebanese government and professional Lebanese army,
which are credible.
</P>
<P>
Syria, the main power broker in Lebanon, has been trying to
link any Israeli withdrawal from Lebanon with a comprehensive
accord that would ensure an Israeli pullout from the Golan
Heights, captured by Israel from Syria in the 1967 Middle East
War.
</P>
<P>
At the press conference, Netanyahu also stressed that the U.N.
can encourage concerned parties to make decisions, but only direct
negotiations can lead to agreements. He denied that there was
some special withdrawal plan that Mordechai had sent to Annan.
</P>
<P>
On the Israeli-Palestinian peace talks, Netanyahu stressed that
every inch territory in the West Bank is tied to Israeli
national interests, and Israel could only carry out the second
redeployment without endangering its security.
</P>
<P>
Annan said that the land of the West Bank is also important to
the Palestinians and the U.N. will help the Palestinians fulfill
their commitments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980325.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Stresses U.S.-African Trade Partnership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 24 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
pledged Tuesday to enact Africa trade bill which had been passed
by the U.S. Congress on March 11, according to a release from
Uganda presidential office.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting with his Ugandan counterpart Yoweri Museveni,
Clinton said he would seek support from multi-national financial
institutions for crucial development sectors in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Under the African trade bill, the total sub-Saharan Africa can
export up to 1.3 billion Dollars of textiles annually to the U.S.
up to 2005. The amount consists of two percent of U.S. textile
import a year.
</P>
<P>
Museveni hailed the U.S. African trade bill as a positive step
in the right direction in the improvement of African access to
the U.S. market.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the Ugandan president also briefed Clinton
on the democratization and governance in Uganda as well as the
country's economic performance with a growth rate of 6.5 percent
in recent years.
</P>
<P>
He assured Clinton of Uganda's commitment to regional
stability, cooperation and integration, said the release.
</P>
<P>
Museveni also asked Clinton to support Africa in its efforts
to attract private businessmen to invest in Africa's
infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
William Daley, the U.S. Secretary of State for Commerce who
was present at the meeting, expressed appreciation over
Museveni's effort to invite investors to Uganda, pledging that
Clinton's visit to Africa would lead to have interest in
investing in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Daley called for the establishment of a technology transfer
center in Uganda. According to him, the United States is
interested in developing air communication in Uganda as an
important aspect of the development of non-traditional export
products.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, U.S. investment in Uganda is centered on
non-agriculture sectors including tourism, mining and
infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
Clinton arrived here early Tuesday morning for a two-day
official visit to Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, the first sitting U.S. president to visit Africa in
two decades, is scheduled to attend a summit Wednesday with 10
regional leaders on peace and prosperity.
</P>
<P>
Uganda is the second leg of his six-nation African tour, which
will also take him to Rwanda, South Africa, Botswana and Senegal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
