<DOCNO> XIE19980325.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Sees Increase in Trade with Brazil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria has recorded increasing
trade with Brazil, with a favorable balance of 311 million U.S.
Dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that Nigeria exported 560 million Dollars'
worth of goods to Brazil last year and imported products valued
at 249 million Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The figure also represents a sharp contrast to that of
bilateral trade in 1996, when Nigeria's imports reached 275
million Dollars and exports at 253 million Dollars.
</P>
<P>
According to the Nigerian-Brazilian Chamber of Commerce and
Industry, crude oil, animal hides and skins, cashew nuts and
natural rubber constituted Nigeria's main export products to
Brazil.
</P>
<P>
Crude oil accounted for about 98.6 percent of Nigeria's
exports to the south American country, the chamber said.
</P>
<P>
The two countries recorded the same trade volume of 528
million Dollars in both 1995 and 1996. But while Nigeria
benefited a favorable balance of 40 million Dollars in 1995, it
posted a deficit of 22 million the following year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
