<DOCNO> XIE19980325.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Insurgents Free 5 Nuns in Northwest Rwanda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Five of the seven nuns who were
abducted Sunday night in Rwanda's northwestern Gisenyi prefecture
by armed Hutu "Interahamwe" militiamen have been released,
official sources in the prefecture said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The five released are Rwandese, the Spaniards are still held
at an unknown location," the office of the Episcopal Conference
of Rwanda (CER) told Rwanda News Agency (RNA) Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The CER office, however, declared that it did not have any
clue about the two Spanish sisters who are still in captivity,
the RNA said in a special dispatch to Xinhua here.
</P>
<P>
There has been no details about the circumstances in which the
five Rwandan nuns were set free.
</P>
<P>
The seven nuns were abducted Sunday night at Kivumu parish, 10
km southwewt of Gisenyi town, near the border with the Democratic
Republic of Congo (DRC) by suspected armed "Interahamwe" militia.
</P>
<P>
Officials in Gisenyi have indicated that the gang that
abducted the nuns came from neighboring Kanama commune, which is
considered a hotbed of the die-hard Hutu extremists.
</P>
<P>
The militiamen reportedly burnt two vehicles, looted the
health center where the nuns were working, and killed seven
people.
</P>
<P>
The militiamen also killed eight people, including two local
government officials.
</P>
<P>
There has been rampant insecurity in northwest Rwanda which is
blamed on Hutu extremists who stand accused of the 1994 genocide
of more than half a million Tutsis and moderate Hutus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
