<HEADLINE> Iraq Slams British Allegation of Flooding West </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Iraq Tuesday slammed British
allegation that it has tried to flood Britain with the lethal
anthrax bottles disguised as duty-free goods should the country
be under military attack by the U.S. and Britain.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that "an all ports warning" was issued by the
British Home Office on the prime minister's orders.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the British allegations, an Iraqi official
spokesman said that Britain which admitted last Monday its forces
used depleted uranium missiles against Iraq in the 1991 Gulf War
is trying today to mislead the public opinion with its
fabrications that Iraq has biological weapons.
</P>
<P>
"These allegations are ridiculous, unfounded and a product of
a diseased mentality," Iraqi News Agency quoted the spokesman as
saying.
</P>
<P>
"It has become typical of Britain and its officials to
fabricate lies against Iraq from time to time in order to appease
the United States in its attempt to prolong the sanctions against
Iraq," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Such claims and falsities could no longer fool anyone as
they lack wisdom, logic and reason," said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. sanctions were imposed on Iraq after its invasion of
Kuwait in 1990. They can only be lifted after U.N. inspectors
verify that Iraq is free of weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Britain had threatened to launch military strike
against Iraq to force entry into Iraqi presidential palaces for
U.N. inspectors. The crisis was defused by an agreement worked out
by U.N. chief Kofi Annan a month ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
