<HEADLINE> Iraq Gives up Efforts to Fly Pilgrims to Saudi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Iraq has given up efforts to win
the approval of the U.N. Sanctions Committee to fly 22,000 Iraqis
to Mecca, Saudi Arabia, to make a pilgrimage early next month, the
Iraqi News Agency reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Ambassador to the United Nations Nizar Hamdoon said in a
letter sent to the committee recently that there was "no longer
any practical usefulness in continuing the discussions of this
matter," because it was too late.
</P>
<P>
He said that since March 23 was the deadline set by Saudi
Arabia for Iraq to notify whether the pilgrims would go by air,
Iraqi pilgrims had no other choice than taking the land route this
year.
</P>
<P>
Hamdoon expressed hope that "beginning from next year Iraqi
pilgrims will be able to perform the rites of their religion
without restrictions."
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Foreign Minister Mohammed Saeed al-Sahhaf put forward the
request to let Iraqi pilgrims travel to Saudi Arabia by air in a
letter to U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan on January 11.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Sanctions Committee has approved to allocate each
Iraqi pilgrim 2,000 U.S. dollars from the proceeds earned by Iraq
under the U.N. oil-for-food deal, which allows Iraq to sell a
limited amount of oil in every six months to afford humanitarian
needs.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been under U.N. sanctions since 1990 after its
invasion of Kuwait. The sanctions ban flights to and from Iraq and
oil exports, its main revenue earner. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
