<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Proposes Aid Programs for African </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Visiting U.S. President Bill
Clinton Tuesday proclaimed three new initiatives for improving
African children's education, nutrition and health during a
speech at a school in Mukono District, central Uganda.
</P>
<P>
The United States will provide about 120 million U.S. Dollars
in 1998 and 1999 to fund for African Education Initiative which
consists of community resource centers, public-private
partnerships and educating and empowering girls in Africa,
Clinton said at Kisowera Primary School in the district.
</P>
<P>
He explained that community resource centers will provide
education materials and serve as bases to improve local teacher
preparation and training for out-of-school youths.
</P>
<P>
School-to-school partnerships between the United States and
Africa, as well as among African schools will also be promoted,
Clinton noted.
</P>
<P>
According to the U.S. president, the education initiative will
fund partnerships between U.S. and African government
institutions and among African government institutions and civil
society organizations.
</P>
<P>
Securing Better Nutrition Initiative, Clinton said, is
designed to assist African countries to strengthen and protect
agriculture and food security in a number of key areas.
</P>
<P>
Implementing this initiative, the American government will
supply 61 million Dollars in the first two years and the fund
will be channeled to the appropriate government and private
sector organizations, said Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Also announced Tuesday was the Infectious Disease Initiative
for Africa, for which the U.S. will grant 16 million Dollars in
the ongoing financial year 1998.
</P>
<P>
Clinton claimed that these initiatives are designed to
underscore the new U.S.-African partnership.
</P>
<P>
Explaining the partnership, Susan Rice, the Assistant
Secretary of State for African Affairs, said on a U.S.
Information Agency World-net TV broadcast on March 19 that it is
suitable to the needs of both Africa and the United States.
</P>
<P>
Clinton arrived here early Tuesday morning for a two-day
official visit to Uganda.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. president is expected to attend a summit in Uganda
Wednesday on peace and prosperity along with 10 regional leaders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
