<DOCNO> XIE19980325.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU, Latin America to Cooperate Further on Drugs Fight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 24 (Xinhua) -- The European Union and Latin
American and Caribbean countries have decided to cooperate further
in their fight against illegal drugs.
</P>
<P>
The decision was taken at a two-day meeting of high-level
officials from these regions that ended Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Those attending the meeting discussed the European Union's
proposal to set up a coordination and cooperation mechanism
between the 15-nation union and the Latin American and Caribbean
countries.
</P>
<P>
The mechanism is designed to deepen political and technical
dialogues between the partners to enhance the existing cooperation
in the fight against drugs and to develop new areas of
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Those present agreed that drugs-fight coordination and
cooperation should be based on the principles of shared
responsibility, integrated and balanced approach, sustainable
development, and in conformity with international law and
particularly with full respect for their sovereignty and
territorial integrity, non-intervention in internal affairs and
human rights.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed to enhance cooperation in such areas as the
cultivation, production and transport of drugs, law enforcement,
government organization, information and intelligence, money
laundering, drugs demand reduction, juvenile crime, synthetic
drugs and illegal arms trafficking.
</P>
<P>
The coordination and cooperation mechanism is expected to be
operational prior to the summit between the European Union and
Latin American and Caribbean countries.
</P>
<P>
The summit meeting is slated for 1999 in Rio de Janeiro,
Brazil. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980325.0083 </DOCNO>
