<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Deported Aliens Could Face Longer Sentences on Re-Entry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 24 (Xinhua) -- The Supreme Court Tuesday made
it easier to impose longer prison sentences on some aliens who
illegally re-enter the United States after being deported.
</P>
<P>
In a 5-4 ruling, the court said aliens who were convicted of a
crime before being deported can be given a longer sentence upon
re-entry even if the previous conviction is not charged and proven
in a new trial.
</P>
<P>
The court upheld a seven-year, one-month prison sentence
ordered for a Mexican citizen, who pleaded guilty in Fort Worth,
Texas, to illegally re-entering the United States in 1995 after
having been deported three years earlier.
</P>
<P>
Federal law sets a maximum two-year sentence for most people
who re-enter illegally after a previous deportation. But another
section of the law allows longer prison terms for those who were
convicted of a crime before their deportation.
</P>
<P>
As Almendarez-Torres had been convicted of burglary three times
before his 1992 deportation, he was given the longer prison
sentence.
</P>
<P>
He appealed, saying prosecutors did not charge him with having
previously been convicted of a crime. He said prosecutors must
charge and prove such convictions beyond a reasonable doubt before
a sentence of more than two years can be imposed.
</P>
<P>
The 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals rejected that argument,
and Tuesday's decision upheld the appeals court ruling. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980325.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
