<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-24 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey, Israel Sign Protocol on Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Turkey and Israel signed a
protocol on trade here Tuesday. The contents of the protocol were
not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
The protocol was signed by Turkish State Minister Isin Celebi
and visiting Israeli Industry and Trade Minister Natan
Sharansky, who arrived Monday for a two-day visit.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting of the joint committee of the Turkish-Israeli
Free Trade Agreement, Celebi said that the trade agreement signed
by Turkey and Israel last year would make great contributions to
the development of bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Sharansky said that the trade agreement has
promoted the rapid development of the economic and trade ties
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Celebi and Sharansky declared in Istanbul, the largest city of
Turkey, on Monday that Turkey and Israel have planned to bolster
annual two-way trade volume from 620.7 million U.S. dollars in
1997 to 2 billion dollars in the coming years.
</P>
<P>
Celebi said that Turkey's trade with Israel increased 38
percent last year over that of 1996 after the signing of the free
trade agreement.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's exports to Israel last year totaled 391.4 million
dollars while its imports from that country stood at 229.3
million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Iron and steel products, cement, woven clothing and synthetic
fibers are Turkey's major exports to Israel. Its leading import
items from Israel include chemical products, plastics, cotton,
seeds and optical equipment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
