<DOCNO> XIE19980325.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-24 20:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey to Extend State of Emergency in Southeast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Turkey decided on Tuesday to
extend the state of emergency in southeastern Turkey for another
four months starting on March 30 in a bid to fight against the
outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK).
</P>
<P>
Six provinces, namely, Diyarbakir, Hakkari, Siirt, Sirnak,
Tunceli and Van, are under the extended emergency rule. The
extension was proposed by the Prime Ministry and approved by the
parliament.
</P>
<P>
Emergency rule has been imposed in Turkey's nine southeastern
provinces since 1987, giving soldiers and police more extensive
powers of arrest and detention in the fight against the PKK. Last
October, three provinces were excluded from the list.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting an almost 14-year-old separatist war
for autonomy in eastern and southeastern Turkey, which has claimed
more than 28,000 lives since August 1984.
</P>
<P>
Some 2,500 to 3,000 PKK militants, who have sheltered
themselves in northern Iraq since the 1991 Gulf War, often cross
into Turkey from northern Iraq and attack military and civilian
targets in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980325.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-24 20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Another Evaluation Meeting on Iraq's Chemical File </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Chairman of the U.N. Special
Commission Richard Butler and Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq
Aziz agreed on Tuesday that another technical evaluation meeting
on Iraq's chemical file will be held soon, UNSCOM spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Zlauvinen Gustavo told Xinhua that Butler and Aziz held their
third and final round of talks Tuesday and discussed the outcome
of the technical evaluation meetings held early February.
</P>
<P>
The previous two rounds of talks were held Monday.
</P>
<P>
Technical evaluation meetings, which are intended to iron out
the differences between the United Nations Special Commission
(UNSCOM) and Iraq, have achieved much progress in files of missile
warheads and chemical agent VX.
</P>
<P>
Gustavo said that another technical evaluation meeting will
focus on VX and its production facilities.
</P>
<P>
Butler did not discuss with Aziz the inspection of Iraq's eight
presidential sites as they will be inspected by a special group
headed by Commissioner Jinayatha Dhanapala, Gustavo said.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement signed last month by the U.N. chief Kofi
Annan and Aziz, Iraq will open the presidential compounds to the
group comprising senior diplomats and experts from the UNSCOM and
the International Atomic Energy Agency.
</P>
<P>
But according to the timetable of Butler, who arrived here last
Sunday on a five-day visit, he will discuss the inspection of the
presidential sites with Dhanapala on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Butler told reporters upon his arrival that there are 1,058
buildings in the presidential sites, and the inspections "will not
take a long time."
</P>
<P>
The UNSCOM must certify that Iraq has destroyed its long-range
missiles and nuclear, chemical and biological weapons before the
U.N. can lift the crippling economic sanctions imposed on Iraq in
1990 after its invasion of Kuwait. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
