<DOCNO> XIE19980325.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Yeltsin Dismisses Government, Aims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
dismissed his entier government Monday, firing his loyal Prime
Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin, immediately after returning to work
in the Kremlin at the end of a week recovery from a throat
infection.
</P>
<P>
This seems to have happened all of a sudden, but the new task
for Chernomyrdin and the quick nomination by the president of the
acting prime minister and acting interior minister have indicated
mature deliberation.
</P>
<P>
It is clear that the dismissal was in preparation for the 2000
presidential elections. "The presidential elections of 2000 are of
primary importance to us. The fate of the country is at stake,"
Yeltsin stressed while announcing the dismissal.
</P>
<P>
The traces are evident. Neither the president nor fired Premier
Chernomyrdin and First Deputy Prime Minister Anatoly Chubais
expressed regret over the dismissal. Chernomyrdin said this is a
natural process of a renewal of authority. He disclosed that it
was his decision to tender resignation and to concentrate on
preparations for the 2000 presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
"Slightly over two years are to go before the presidential
elections. I can't remain indifferent to the future of the
country," he explained.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin's decision was "strongly supported" by the
president, who announced Monday that the resigned prime minister
must "concentrate on political preparations" for the 2000
presidential elections. Meanwhile, Yeltsin awarded his trusted
premier a second class order "for services to the fatherland."
</P>
<P>
Chubais was even satisfied with his discharge, saying, "I'm
glad that the president has granted my request for quitting the
government service with which I addressed him last month."
</P>
<P>
According to Chubais, the decision taken by the president to
dismiss the Cabinet has been prepared long. He said that he will
still be in the team of Yeltsin no matter in which capacity and
where he works.
</P>
<P>
Soon after announcing the dismissal of the government, Yeltsin,
on the same day, appointed 35-year-old Sergei Kiriyenko, the
former fuel and energy minister, acting prime minister and Pavel
Maslov, the former first deputy interior minister and chief of
staff of the Interior Ministry, acting interior minister.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin has repeatedly criticized the government's ministers
for failure to pay pensions and wages on time. The president in
his state-of-the-nation speech on February 17 said that if the
wages and pensions payment -- one of the top priorities -- wasn't
fulfilled, "we will have a new government."
</P>
<P>
The firings were "an effort to bring more energy and efficiency
to economic reforms, to give them additional impetus," said
Yeltsin after the government was dismissed.
</P>
<P>
The "key social problems" might seriously shake the government
and then the presidential throne so that the political and
economic orientation held by the Russian leadership would be
altered.
</P>
<P>
It was known that the Trade Union and the Communist Party are
preparing a nationwide protest to place a no-confidence motion
before the government.
</P>
<P>
Leader Gennady Zyuganov, knowing the government's dismissal,
said that if the government had not resigned, the trade union and
the left-initiated protest actions scheduled for April 9 would
take its resignation as their main slogan.
</P>
<P>
According to Russian Duma Chairman Gennady Seleznyov, during an
all-Russia action of protest set for April 9, "most working people
would have demanded the resignation of the government."
</P>
<P>
Perhaps, it was wise for Yeltsin to dismiss the government
ahead of time, and with the situation developing, there will be a
possibility of dismissing the Communists-dominated State Duma. If
it failed to approve a new prime minister for three times running,
new parliament elections would be held. Then, it might be easier
to win the presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
However, the details of the president's plan remain a mystery
as to whom Yeltsin wants to run for the presidency in the 2000.
Chernomyrdin remarked he had not decided about the presidential
run. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980325.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
