<HEADLINE> Former FBI Agent Claims Possession of Documents on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 24 (Xinhua) -- A former Federal Bureau of
Investigation agent who impounded James Earl Ray's car after the
1968 assassination of civil rights leader Martin Luther King Jr.
said Tuesday he kept two slips of paper from the car that may
bolster Ray's claim of a conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
Donald Wilson discussed the documents Tuesday with District
Attorney Paul Howard of Fulton County, Georgia, and later told
reporters he wanted to give them directly to U.S. Attorney General
Janet Reno, The Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
Wilson, then an agent with the FBI office in Atlanta, was one
of the two agents who impounded Ray's white Ford Mustang at an
Atlanta housing project on April 10, 1968, six days after King was
assassinated in Memphis.
</P>
<P>
The Atlanta Journal-Constitution reported Tuesday that one of
the papers he found is an itemized list of names, locations and
figures that appear to be dollar amounts. At the bottom, the
figure 450,000.00 is written along with a date and a word that
appears to be Raul.
</P>
<P>
The other contains a telephone number and the name Raul, the
newspaper said. The newspaper did not give any of the other names.
</P>
<P>
Ray, who pleaded guilty in 1969 but then recanted and has been
seeking a trial ever since, has claimed he was set up by a shadowy
gunrunner he knew only as Raoul. No independent evidees in the Chicago area, sai
d he had the original
documents in a vault there.
</P>
<P>
The Journal-Constitution said Wilson did not pass the documents
to his superiors in 1968 because he did not believe they were
conducting a serious investigation and did not trust them. He said
he decided last year to share them with King's relatives, who are
supporting Ray's efforts to win a trial.
</P>
<P>
Wilson was accompanied to the courthouse by William Pepper, an
attorney trying to win a trial for Ray. Pepper said he urged
Wilson to come forward now because Ray is seriously ill from liver
disease and may not live much longer.
</P>
<P>
Cartha DeLoach, who was assistant to FBI Director J. Edgar
Hoover in 1968, said he was not aware of Wilson's evidence.
</P>
<P>
"I doubt very seriously that is true," he told the newspaper
from Hilton Head Island, South Carolina, where he lives.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
