<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cohen: Expert Arrest Shows Iraqi Attempt to Hide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 24 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Defense Secretary William
Cohen said Tuesday that the arrest of an Iraqi biological weapons
expert by the Iraq government indicated Iraq's attempt to hide
weapons information.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times reported Tuesday that Iraqi scientist Nassir
Hindawi was arrested because he had planned to defect.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted Iraq's U.N. Ambassador Nizar Hamdoon as
saying that Nassir Hindawi, one of the founders of the Iraqi germ
warfare program, was in an Iraqi prison after he was found with
documents relating to the country's biological weapons program and
evidence that he was about to leave Iraq illegally.
</P>
<P>
Cohen said Iraq's step to arrest Nassir Hindawi might be
further evidence "that there is an attempt on the part of (Iraqi
President) Saddam Hussein to continue to hide and prevent UNSCOM
inspectors from receiving information that would help them in
their business."
</P>
<P>
Cohen, who spoke to reporters at the Pentagon, said the Iraqi
action could make it even more difficult for Iraq to convince the
United Nations of its full compliance with weapons inspections and
to win a lifting of sanctions imposed after the 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
He stressed Iraq must provide not only claims but concrete
evidence that Iraq has ended a program to develop chemical and
biological weapons before U.N. sanctions against Iraq are lifted.
</P>
<P>
Cohen declined to say whether U.S. intelligence organizations
had assisted the Iraqi expert in his attempt to leave his country.
</P>
<P>
Neither would he comment on whether the arrest of "this
particular individual would be an intelligency loss to the United
States." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980325.0095 </DOCNO>
