<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 15:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait Receives Compensation Money for Loss in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, March 25 (Xinhua) -- A total of 170 million
U.S. dollars of compensation money has been transferred to Kuwait
from the United Nations Compensations Commission (UNCC) for loss
during the Gulf crisis from 1990 to 1991.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti Deputy Prime Minister and State Minister for Cabinet
Affairs Nasser Abdallah Al-Roudhan said Wednesday that the money
would be used to cover compensation due to the third group of
claimants under categories A and C.
</P>
<P>
The Kuwaiti Public Authority for the Assessment of
Compensations (PAAC) would transfer the money to the bank accounts
of those entitled as specified in the applications submitted by
them earlier, he added.
</P>
<P>
The beneficiaries would be the third batch of claimants under
category A who left Kuwait during the Iraqi invasion of the
country in 1990 and category C whose individual loss caused by the
Gulf War in 1991 was below 100,000 dollars.
</P>
<P>
Al-Roudhan said payment would start after coordination with
the parties concerned, but he did not give the number of people to
be compensated.
</P>
<P>
Last October, the second batch of a total of 224,841
claimants, among them 42,148 Kuwaitis, were benefited from a 105
million dollars compensation out of a total of 596 million dollars
compensation funds set aside from Iraq's oil exports revenues.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait received the first batch of compensation money, about
123 million dollars, from the UNCC for its categories A and C
claimants at the start of 1997.
</P>
<P>
The money was obtained after Iraq started selling oil under the
Iraq-U.N. oil-for-food deal, which allowed it to sell 2 billion
dollars worth of oil over six months for humanitarian purpose.
</P>
<P>
About 30 percent of the Iraqi oil sales proceeds was paid into
the compensation fund run by the Geneva-based U.N. Compensation
Commission which in turn transferred the money to Kuwaiti as well
as other claimants.
</P>
<P>
So far Iraq has provided about 1.2 billion dollars to the
U.N. compensation fund under the deal.
</P>
<P>
More than 800,000 men and women from 78 countries were
demanding a total of 3.2 billion dollars in compensation stemming
mainly from lost wages, damages and injures.
</P>
<P>
As to the whole compensation demands, Kuwait alone had filed
claims totaling 130 billion dollars, including the costs of
extinguishing oil well fires that had been set by Iraqi troops
before a U.S.-led military coalition chased them out of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Corporations from around the world were seeking another 80
billion dollars in compensation.
</P>
<P>
According to regulations set by the commission, the claims were
divided into six categories. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
