<DOCNO> XIE19980325.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 15:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanese PM Visits Austria for Better Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik
Hariri left here for Vienna Wednesday afternoon on an official
two-day visit to Austria aimed at promoting cooperation between
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Hariri is expected to hold talks with Austria's Chancellor
Viktor Klima and other top officials on the situation in the
Middle East region and means of boosting bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
Austria will take up the post of the European Union (EU)
presidency in June and is likely to play an active role in helping
reactivate the Middle East peace process, which has been
deadlocked since a year ago due to Israel's construction of a
Jewish settlement.
</P>
<P>
Hariri's visit will serve to promote the existing cooperation
between the EU and Lebanon and seek financial contributions to the
country's reconstruction projects, observers said.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese prime minister will brief Austrian businessmen on
investment prospects and Lebanon's reconstruction efforts to
encourage foreign investment to develop tourism and medium-sized
industries.
</P>
<P>
He is scheduled to give two lectures to Austrian Committee for
Foreign and International Affairs and the Lebanese-Austrian
Committee. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980325.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chronic Diseases: Biggest Killer in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 25 (Xinhua) -- About 13,000 people are killed
every day in China by cardiovascular and cerebral diseases,
cancers and diabetes, the Chinese Ministry of Health announced
here today.
</P>
<P>
The illnesses, defined as "non-infectious chronic diseases",
have become the biggest killer in the country, causing 70 percent
of its total death cases, the ministry said in a report.
</P>
<P>
"China has at least 90 million hypertension patients, 20
million diabetes patients and six million sufferers of
stroke. Cancer cases are increasing by 1.6 million a year," it
said.
</P>
<P>
Incidence rates of the diseases in urban and rural areas were
28.6 percent and 13 percent respectively, a rise of 14 percent and
44 percent over the levels of 1985.
</P>
<P>
Experts predicted that medical expenditures would surpass 120
billion yuan (14.4 billion US dollars) by the year 2000, compared
with 41.9 billion yuan (five billion dollars) in 1994.
</P>
<P>
They blamed the rapid epidemic of the diseases on
hereditary reasons, environmental pollution, some
improper life styles and behaviors, such as smoking, excessive
drinking, and the lack of physical exercises.
</P>
<P>
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
