<HEADLINE> Du Pont Company Hopes to Expand Cooperation with China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 25 (Xinhua) -- US-based Du Pont Company plans to
expand its traditional areas of cooperation with China to include
biotechnology, according to Charles Holliday Jr., the company's
new president and CEO.
</P>
<P>
Holliday told reporters attending today's press conference that
Du Pont's new development direction will center on combining
the traditional chemical industry with biotechnology.
</P>
<P>
He pointed to Du Pont's leading position in plant gene
queue technology, and noted that the company has recorded
major progress in related research. He also noted that the Chinese
government has expressed great interest in cooperating with Du
Pont in the realm of biotechnology.
</P>
<P>
Holliday said the company and German-based Basf company have
inked an agreement to produce nylon intermediates in a new plant
to be constructed in south China's Hainan Province.
</P>
<P>
The plant will manufacture products which will meet the
increasing demand on the Chinese market and will be exported to
factories in Singapore and the United States.
</P>
<P>
He said that approval by the Chinese government will enable
construction to begin at the end of this year and the plant will
enter operations in the year 2002.
</P>
<P>
The company also plans to open a Shanghai technology center in
July, and will establish an enterprise in Shenzhen to provide
Teflon, Silverstone and coatings to household equipment and
industrial manufacturers in China and other countries in the
Asia-Pacific Region.
</P>
<P>
He described the concrete steps as part of Du Pont's commitment
to invest up to one billion US dollars in China by the year
2000. "We are confident of achieving the goal," said Holliday.
</P>
<P>
Du Pont has invested 300 million US dollars in China to
establish ten-odd joint ventures and solely-funded enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Du Pont recored a 10 percent rise in business volume in China
for 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
