<HEADLINE> Romania Hopes to Gain More From Trade With Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Romanian businessmen are
scrutinizing Asian markets in the hope of boosting trade with the
continent.
</P>
<P>
"There is a strong political willingness to strengthen
relations with the Asian countries", said Nicu Manolache, who is
in charge of Asian affairs in the Romanian Ministry of Industry
and Trade.
</P>
<P>
"Asia could become Romania's most important commercial partner
and offer it a solution for boosting its export trade", he said in
the latest Economic Truth weekly.
</P>
<P>
Manolache admitted that the Asian financial troubles have
stripped Romanian products of a sustainable market and that many
Romanian companies have brought their production to a halt to
reduce further losses.
</P>
<P>
But in spite of this, he noted, Romania scored a noticeable
rise in trade with Indonesia, with exports totalling 53 million
U.S. dollars in 1997, up from 16 million dollars the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Chemical products, bearings, machinery, chassis, tractors and
Dacia-brand cars all contribute to Romanian export trade with
Asian states.
</P>
<P>
Several Romanian companies have entered partnerships with the
Japanese to engineer projects for building cement and glass mills
in Pakistan and the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
The Romanian Government also plans to strengthen cooperation
with Hanoi authorities by setting in place a refinery in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
"We hope to gain at least 10 percent more from our trade with
Asia, which compels us to diversify", Manolache said, citing that
wine, furniture and paper as new products bound for Asian
markets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
