<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: 11 EU Member States Recommended for EMU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 25 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission has
recommended 11 European Union member states for the founding of
the European single currency.
</P>
<P>
The recommendation was made during a special meeting of the
European Parliament, to which the commission, the executive body
of the 15-nation union, presented its report on economic
convergence.
</P>
<P>
Belgium, Germany, Spain, France, Ireland, Italy, Luxembourg,
the Netherlands, Austria, Portugal and Finland were recommended as
having met the necessary conditions to adopt the single currency,
the Euro, on January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Britain, serving the six-month rotating presidency of the
union, and Denmark exercised their right under the Maastricht
Treaty to opt out of the first wave for the Economic and Monetary
Union (EMU) while Greece and Sweden were judged by the commission
not economically ready to join.
</P>
<P>
To qualify for the final stage of EMU, European Union member
states must attain a high degree of sustainable economic
convergence.
</P>
<P>
Progress is measured against key criteria covering inflation,
government deficit and debt, exchange rate stability and long-term
interest rates.
</P>
<P>
Member states must also meet other conditions such as central
bank independence.
</P>
<P>
The commission already adopted the recommendation of the 11
countries on the initiative of Commission President Jacques Santer
and Commissioner Yves-Thibault de Silguy who is responsible for EU
economic, monetary and financial affairs.
</P>
<P>
The European Union heads of state and government will confirm
the list of the first-wave of EMU countries on May 2 during their
summit for the first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
Their confirmation will be made on the basis of the
commission's recommendation and its convergence report along with
another convergence report prepared by the European Monetary
Institute.
</P>
<P>
The final decision will be taken on a recommendation from the
EU Council of Economy and Finance Ministers after consulting the
European Parliament.
</P>
<P>
When the 11 recommended countries are confirmed for
participation by the EU summit in Brussels, this will create a
Euro-zone with nearly 300 million inhabitants accounting for 19.4
percent of world gross domestic product (GDP) and 18.6 percent of
world trade.
</P>
<P>
This compares with 19.6 percent of world GDP and 16.6 percent
of world trade for the United States and 7.7 percent of world GDP
and 8.2 percent of world trade for Japan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980325.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Announces List of Likely EMU Participants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 25 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission on
Wednesday announced its recommendation of 11 European Union member
states as likely founder countries of the single currency.
</P>
<P>
The recommendation was made during the day's special hearing of
the European Parliament, to which the commission, the executive
body of the 15-nation union, presented its report on economic
convergence.
</P>
<P>
Belgium, Germany, Spain, France, Ireland, Italy, Luxembourg,
the Netherlands, Austria, Portugal and Finland were recommended as
having met the set conditions to adopt the euro on January 1,
1999.
</P>
<P>
Britain, which is serving the six-month rotating presidency of
the union, together with Denmark opted out of the first wave for
the Economic and Monetary Union (EMU) while Greece and Sweden were
judged by the commission as not economically ready.
</P>
<P>
Commission President Jacques Santer described the announcement
as something impossible to think of a year ago while Yves-Thibault
de Silguy, commissioner responsible for economic, monetary and
financial affairs, said that the announcement of the list was not
the result of coincidence but results of political will and hard
work for the past few years.
</P>
<P>
To qualify for the final stage of EMU, European Union member
states must attain a high degree of sustainable economic
convergence.
</P>
<P>
Progress is measured against key criteria covering inflation,
government deficit and debt, exchange rate stability and long-term
interest rates. The criteria were set up by the Maastricht Treaty
reached in December 1991.
</P>
<P>
Member states must also meet certain other conditions such as
central bank independence.
</P>
<P>
The commission has adopted the recommendation of the 11
countries on the initiative of Santer and de Silguy.
</P>
<P>
The European Union heads of state and government will confirm
the list of the first-wave EMU participating countries on May 2
during their summit for the first half of the year.
</P>
<P>
Their confirmation will be made on the basis of the
commission's recommendation and its convergence report along with
another convergence report prepared by the European Monetary
Institute.
</P>
<P>
The final decision will be taken on a recommendation from the
EU council of economy and finance ministers (ECOFIN) after
consulting the European Parliament.
</P>
<P>
Santer stressed that the summit meeting would also select the
head of the future European central bank and fill the seats on its
executive committee as well.
</P>
<P>
When the 11 recommended countries are confirmed for
participation by the EU summit, they will create a euro-zone with
nearly 300 million inhabitants accounting for 19.4 percent of
world gross domestic product (GDP) and 18.6 percent of world
trade.
</P>
<P>
This compares with 19.6 percent of world GDP and 16.6 percent
of world trade for the United States and 7.7 percent of world GDP
and 8.2 percent of world trade for Japan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980325.0108 </DOCNO>
