<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: EMU Convergence Criteria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 25 (Xinhua) -- The European Union defined five
key criteria for the economic convergence for Economic and
Monetary Union at its Maastricht summit in December 1991.
</P>
<P>
The criteria are: inflation; budget deficit as against gross
domestic product (GDP); public debt as against GDP; exchange rate
stability; and long-term interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The reference values for each criterion, except for deficit and
debt, is calculated in accordance with certain formula.
</P>
<P>
The criterion for inflation or price stability is calculated by
adding to the average of the three EU member states with lowest
figures two percentage points. The current reference value for this
category is 2.7 percent for January 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Maastricht Treaty has laid down a constant
three-percent-of-GDP target for budget deficit and a constant
60-percent-of-GDP ratio for public debt.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission has devised an average currency for the
purpose of reviewing exchange rate stability. The average is the
one that may be found at any time in the middle of the fluctuating
band that can vary over time.
</P>
<P>
All currencies except for Irish punt have fluctuated within a
band of 2.25 percent either side of the parity throughout the
EU-designated consideration period from March 1996 to February
1998.
</P>
<P>
Britain and Sweden are not taking part in the exchange rate
mechanism of the European monetary system.
</P>
<P>
The reference level for long-term interest rates cannot be two
percent more than the average inflation rate achieved by the three
best-performing EU countries. This criteria is set at 7.8
percent for January this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980325.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 15:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Parliament Speaker Accuses U.N. of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Knesset (parliament)
Speaker Dan Tichon accused the United Nations of adopting a
hostile policy towards Israel on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a Knesset special session organized for visiting
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, Tichon said that the U.N. has
taken a biased hostile approach towards Israel.
</P>
<P>
"The United Nations has never agreed to the establishment of
the Jewish state," Tichon said, adding that "the United
Nations did not play its role in the peace process."
</P>
<P>
Tichon was the first Israeli politician to criticize the United
Nations during Annan's current visit to Israel. The attack caused
angry responses from the Knesset opposition members who charged
that Tichon has humiliated Annan in public.
</P>
<P>
Tichon's remarks reflected Israel's angry towards the U.N.'s
criticism of Israel's settlement activities in the occupied
Palestinian territories.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. General Assembly on March 17 voted 120-3 a resolution
condemning Israeli settlement activities in the occupied
Palestinian territories, including Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Annan later told reporters that he would ask Israel to change
its hostile attitude towards the U.N..
</P>
<P>
"I will reply to Tichon's remarks later in the evening in my
press conference, but I would like to point out that Israel must
learn how to make rooms for the others," he said.
</P>
<P>
"In today's interdependent world, without making rooms for the
others, there will be nothing," Annan said.
</P>
<P>
He also said that Israel must open its mind to the relationship
with the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Annan arrived here on Tuesday from Gaza for a three-day visit
and had already held talks with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu and Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai on how to move
the Middle East peace process forward.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief's current Middle East tour has taken him to
Jordan, Egypt, Lebanon, Syria and Palestinian self-rule areas.
</P>
</TEXT>
