<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Nations Urged to Continue Fiscal Austerity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 25 (Xinhua) -- The European Monetary Institute
(EMI) on Wednesday urged EU nations recommended for the single
European currency next year to continue their fiscal austerity in
order to ensure a strong Euro.
</P>
<P>
"Despite recent success, further intensive fiscal consolidation
is required in almost all member states," said the EMI in a report
on the Euro candidacy presented Wednesday in Frankfurt.
</P>
<P>
The EMI report followed another issued by the European
Commission in Brussels earlier Wednesday which recommended 11 EU
countries for next year's launch of the Euro.
</P>
<P>
The list includes all EU members except Greece, which is far
from reaching the fiscal standards required by the Maastricht
Treaty for Euro membership, and Denmark, Britain and Sweden, who
all opted not to join the Euro in the first wave.
</P>
<P>
The EMI, which is the frontrunner for the planned European
Central Bank, also expressed particular worry about the fiscal
fitness of Italy and Belgium, noting that their high debt levels
were "a cause for concern".
</P>
<P>
Italy and Belgium had national debts of over 120 percent of
gross domestic product (GDP) last year, more than double the
60 percent limit set by the Maastricht Treaty.
</P>
<P>
The EMI said that in order to cut their debt levels, Italy
would have to start showing significant and sustained budget
surpluses while Belgium should have to achieve a budget surplus of
at least six percent of GDP every year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
