reductions in output, but some industry experts believe that the
supply cuts will prove to be far smaller than expected.
</P>
<P>
-- Smoking costs the U.S. about 130 billion U.S. dollars a year
in shortened working lives and added health-care spending, says a
new Treasury analysis that is part of a White House effort to push
tobacco legislation through Congress. 
