<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: South Asia Striving to Control Tuberculosis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, March 25 (Xinhua) -- South Asia, a region most
vulnerable to the attack of tuberculosis (TB) in the world, is
striving to get rid of the scourge, where the seven countries have
all identified TB control as a priority area.
</P>
<P>
According to the estimates by the World Health Organization
(WHO), more than three million new TB cases occur in this region
every year with an annual death of one million patients.
</P>
<P>
And 40 percent of the 1.2 billion population in the region, one
of the poorest in the world, is infected with TB bacillus.
</P>
<P>
This situation will worsen further with the emergence of TB/HIV
co-infection and multi-drug resistant TB, experts have warned.
</P>
<P>
Bearing in mind the huge burden of TB, the South Asian
Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC) has been according a
high priority to TB control and established the SAARC Tuberculosis
Center in 1992 in Bhaktapur, one of the three cities in the
Kathmandu Valley of Nepal.
</P>
<P>
The main objective of the center is to work toward prevention
and control of TB in the region by coordinating the efforts of the
national TB programs of the member countries -- Bangladesh,
Bhutan, India, the Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan and Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
The center collects, analyzes and disseminates all relevant
information regarding the latest development and findings in the
field of TB in the region and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
It also conducts survey, research and training programs for the
purpose of TB control and strive for adequate supply at low cost
of anti-TB drugs and other related supplies in all the member
countries.
</P>
<P>
"Our objective is to cure 85 percent of the cured at least and
find out 70 percent of the existing cases, and of course to
implement DOTS (Directly Observed Treatment Short-course) in each
level everywhere," said Dr. Dirgh Singh Bam, the center's
director.
</P>
<P>
DOTS now is proved the most effective means to control TB, he
said, adding that it is being implemented in all the seven SAARC
member countries though in limited areas.
</P>
<P>
The implementation of DOTS along with national TB programs and
political commitment in the member countries and a cure rate of
more than 85 percent were listed by Dr. Prablad Kumar, deputy
director of the center, as the three achievements made in the
region in the past years.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Kumar attributed the high incidence of TB cases in the
region to overpopulation, high illiteracy rate, poverty and poor
sanitation.
</P>
<P>
He said in efforts to fight TB, the SAARC TB Center has
developed cooperation with the WHO and the International Union
Against Tuberculosis and Lung Diseases, a non-governmental
organization based in Paris.
</P>
<P>
He said the biggest problem facing the region is the dropout of
patients. He explained that the DOTS required a long duration, but
when they feel better, some patients discontinue the treatment.
</P>
<P>
"We're trying to change the behavior of the patients by
strengthening the information, education and communication
system," he said. "Literacy rate is not very high in the region."
</P>
<P>
But he said the rate of dropout has dropped from 50 percent to
15 percent.
</P>
<P>
Practical measures, strong commitment of governments, good
training system, good logistic system, and monitoring and
supervision system are all necessary for effective control of TB,
Dr. Bam added.
</P>
<P>
He noted that in the region there are many big countries and so
many problems including political problems, so the SAARC has set
no deadline for wiping out TB from the region. "It's very
difficult," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
