<HEADLINE> Chinese Defense Minister Meets Venezuelan Visitor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Defense Minister Chi
Haotian met today with Raul Salazar, chairman of the Venezuelan
Joint Chiefs of Staff.
</P>
<P>
Chi said the two countries share many things in common and are
free of conflicts concerning fundamental interests. He noted that
the two nations pursue independent foreign policies of peace,
cherish a peaceful international environment, and propose a
multipolar world.
</P>
<P>
The similarities have enabled the two countries and their
citizens to establish close contacts, said Chi, who also serves as
vice-chairman of the Central Military Commission and State
councilor.
</P>
<P>
He noted the smooth development of bilateral ties since the
establishment of diplomatic relations some 20-odd years ago.
</P>
<P>
Chi said that the exchange of visits between leaders of the two
nations and their armed forces has greatly promoted bilateral
relations.
</P>
<P>
He said Salazar's current China visit will raise
military-to-military relations to a new plateau.
</P>
<P>
Chi also expressed appreciation for Venezuela's adherence to
the "one China" policy, and briefed Salazar on the first session
of the Ninth National People's Congress, as well as China's
defense policy.
</P>
<P>
Salazar praised China's achievements and noted that Venezuelan
citizens firmly believe their country can learn from China's long
history.
</P>
<P>
Salazar also praised the high quality of the Chinese People's
Liberation Army (PLA), and expressed confidence that the
Chinese army will achieve even greater progress.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the Venezuelan government attaches great
importance to developing relations with China, and that the
Venezuelan armed forces hope to establish even closer ties with
the PLA. 
</P>
