<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Economic Review: Optimistic Outlook for 1998 Exports (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
By Xinhua Writer Zhou Zongmin and Wang Weiping
</P>
<P>
BEIJING, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Opportunities provided by the
ongoing financial crisis in Southeast Asia far outweigh challenges
China faces in boosting exports.
</P>
<P>
"The adoption of tangible measures will ensure bright
prospects for the export trade," said Zhao Jinping, a
professor with the State Council Development Research Center.
</P>
<P>
Experts noted that priority should be placed on optimizing the
export commodity structure, expanding exchanges with traditional
customers, especially those in European and American countries,
and developing new markets in Latin America, the Middle East and
Africa.
</P>
<P>
East Asia and Southeast Asia are regarded as major export
markets for China, with exports to the regions accounting for more
than 30 percent of the annual total.
</P>
<P>
The financial crisis which has engulfed Southeast Asia since
July last year and accompanying currency devaluations have created
tense financial conditions and economic difficulties causing many
countries to limit imports and increase exports.
</P>
<P>
Liang Yanfen, a researcher from the International
Trade and Economic Cooperation Institute, notes that China shares
similar export structures with many countries affected by the
crisis. China will thus face fierce competition in terms of export
markets.
</P>
<P>
Declining worldwide economic growth represents yet another
negative element affecting China's exports, and China must adopt
flexible industrial, product and enterprise development policies
to offset the adverse influences, according to Zhang Hanlin, a
professor with the University of International Business and
Economics.
</P>
<P>
Export trade is a major factor for China's economic growth. It
added two percentage points to China's GDP growth last
year. Therefore, experts say, the performance of export trade will
be an important factor for China to achieve the eight-percent
economic growth rate set for 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980325.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Economic Review: Optimistic Outlook for 1998 Exports (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
By Xinhua Writer Zhou Zongmin and Wang Weiping
</P>
<P>
China was one of the world's top ten trading nations in
1997, with the total import-export volume of 325 billion US dollars,
including exports of 182.7 billion US dollars, up 21 percent on
the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The 1998 target has been set 345 billion US dollars, an
increase of 20 billion dollars on the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Many economists predict that this year's exports will grow by
10 percent, a level which they say is possible despite the
decreasing export growth rate.
</P>
<P>
They point out existing difficulties, but also cite increasing
chances for promoting exports.
</P>
<P>
"Advantages continue to hold a dominant position," said Zhao
Jinping. Firstly, according to Zhao, China's major export markets
will continue to enjoy brisk demands in 1998, with the U.S. economy
expected to grow 2.7 percent and the European economy 2.5
percent. Secondly, Chinese enterprises, in face of sluggish
domestic demands, will continue to increase exports. Thirdly,
relatively low inflation will limit the chances for significant
cost increases for export products.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the fact that the exchange rate for the Renminbi
will remain relatively stable will enable Chinese entherprises to
increase exports and focus direct investments in areas such as
Latin America and Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
Another advantage which will help expand exports lies in
China's high-quality, low-cost labor force.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has already introduced a series of
policies to encourage exports, including increased export
credits and simplified export procedures.
</P>
<P>
The first two months of this year witnessed strong momentum in
export increases, especially to the European and American markets.
</P>
<P>
Experts also note that interest rate reductions for bank
deposits and loans, announced yestherday by the People's Bank of
China, will help enterprises boost exports.  Endithem

nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
