<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Launches New Policy on China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 25 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission (EC)
proposed on Wednesday to hold annual summit meetings with China as
part of a new policy to strengthen relations.
</P>
<P>
The policy outlines summit meetings involving China, the EC
and the EU presidency, and regular meetings of senior officials.
</P>
<P>
The new EU-China policy was deemed by EC officials to be a
wide-ranging reappraisal of bilateral relations in view of China's
growing importance on the world stage.
</P>
<P>
EC Vice-President Sir Leon Brittan said: "China's growing
economic and political self-confidence is an overwhelming positive
development.
</P>
<P>
"It should serve as an incentive for the European Union to
engage the country more fully, not as a threat from which to
retreat."
</P>
<P>
The EC agreed to elevate EU's political relations with China to
the status accorded to Beijing by the United States, Japan and
Russia.
</P>
<P>
The new policy took its form in an EC document entitled
Building a Comprehensive Partnership With China. The document was
approved by the commission in its weekly meeting on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Brittan said that Europe has everything to gain and nothing to
fear from a strong, open and prosperous China.
</P>
<P>
The key was to ensure the successful and lasting integration of
China as an equal partner in the world economy, coupled with an
active commitment to creating a strong and open civil society, he
added.
</P>
<P>
The commissioners also agreed that the scale and speed of
China's economic growth are making the country one of Europe's
major economic partners.
</P>
<P>
The EU, therefore, should assist the process of China's global
integration through a mixture of trade policy and tailored
cooperation initiatives.
</P>
<P>
It was also agreed that the EU should continue supporting
China's transition to an open society through promoting the rule
of law and strengthening civil society.
</P>
<P>
The EC believed it was necessary to improve the efficiency and
impact of EU funding in China without increasing the budget. The
EU should consider greater involvement of the European Investment
Bank in China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
