<HEADLINE> Opportunities Accompany Good Momentum of Sino-U.S. Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Foreign Minister Tang
Jiaxuan said today that the good momentum of Sino-U.S. is
accompanied by good opportunities for further improvement and
development.
</P>
<P>
Tang made the remark today during a meeting with Acting
Undersecretary of State John Holum, who arrived in Beijing for
another in a series of regular sub-cabinet level discussions
covering wide-ranging areas, including political, military,
security and arms control issues.
</P>
<P>
Tang stressed that maintaining and developing healthy and
stable Sino-US relations protects the fundamental interests of
both nations.
</P>
<P>
He said China and the United States are finalizing detailed
preparations for the forthcoming state visit by President Bill
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Tang pointed out that China and the United States share many
common concerns regarding the nonproliferation of weapons of mass
destruction, but he also noted that some differences remain with
regard to the issue.
</P>
<P>
China is fully prepared to join the U.S. in discussions carried
out on the basis of equality and mutual respect in order to
enhance understanding, expand common ground, develop cooperation
and safeguard international peace and security.
</P>
<P>
Holum said the current trip is part of preparations for
President Clinton's scheduled visit.
</P>
<P>
He added that the United States hopes to strengthen cooperation
with China in preventing the proliferation of weapons of mass
destruction, and in developing space technology.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the U.S is willing to work closely with China to
ensure the success of President Clinton's visit.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Vice-Foreign Minister Zhang Deguang and Holum today
held discussions centering on international arms control and
security issues. They will continue such discussions on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Vice-Foreign Minister Yang Jiechi met with Holum this
afternoon. Xiong Guangkai, deputy chief of the general staff of
the People's Liberation Army (PLA), is scheduled to meet with U.S
delegation on Thursday. 
</P>
