<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's World Cup Champion Kicked out of National Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
By Yang Ming
</P>
<P>
BEIJING, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Zhao Yongsheng, winner of the
 men's 50-kilometer event at the 1995 World Cup Walking
Championships, was kicked out of the Chinese national track and
field team and lost his right to compete in this year's Asian
Games after breaking disciplines and rules.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Athletics Management Center, the national governing
body of the sports, made an official announcement here on
Wednsday, saying that Zhao's registeration as an athlete has been
suspended and his right to compete in the 12th Asian Games this
December in Bangkok has been stripped off.
</P>
<P>
CAMC said:" Zhao has refused to compete in any races since last
July. He even skipped the Eighth National Games. Moreover, he
broke the team's disciplines by signing contracts in secret with
three different clubs for higher salary and better fringe benefit."
</P>
<P>
"He even instigated reveral team members to escape from the
team. His actions violated the rules and regulations he should
obey," the announcement pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Zhao, 28, twice national champion and the Asian record holder,
led most of the race in the 1995 World Championships, but
eventually collapsed with heat exhaustion in the final stage. He
didn't finish the race again in the Olympics last year.
</P>
<P>
It was learned that Gao Hongmiao, women's 10 kilometer winner
of the 1995 World Cup Walking Championships, also followed Zhao in
sneaking out of the national team last year to pursuit higher
salary and extra housing. But the 24-year-old Gao has escaped
from the punishment.
</P>
<P>
Zhao told the other side of the story by saying that he left
the team only because his previous coach Wang Kui set up an
international walking club last year. After Wang retired, Zhao
showed his concern for the old man, so he joined him.
</P>
<P>
"I don't know what the registeration is all about. I didn't
realize that I infringed some regulations. I only heard that if an
athlete quits competition for a whole year, he will be free to go
wheresoever he like, " Zhao argued.
</P>
<P>
In China, an athlete must be registered in the Chinese
Athletics Association. Without it, he or she has no right to
compete in any races both domestic and abroad. 
</P>
</TEXT>
