<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia's External debt Manageable: Bank Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia will be able to
meet its external financial obligations from export earnings
although debt in ringgit terms has increased significantly as a
result of the weakening of the local currency, the State Bank said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's total medium- and long-term external debt at the end
of 1997 was 32.5 billion U.S. dollars or 34.7 percent of gross
national product (GNP) in US dollar terms or 48 percent of GNP in
ringgit terms, which is low by international standards due to the
low external indebtedness of the federal government, the central
bank said in its 1997 annual report released here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Including the short-term external debt of both the banks and
non-banking private sector, Malaysia's external debt amounted to
42.7 billion U.S. dollars or 45.6 percent of GNP in US dollar
terms or 63.2 percent of GNP in ringgit terms, the central bank
said.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's debt service ratio was 5.7 percent in 1997 compared
with 6.1 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The short-term debt, meanwhile, remained small at about 24
percent of total debt, reflecting the low reliance on short-term
borrowing by the non-banking private sector, it said, adding "The
bulk of the short-term debt was borrowing by the commercial banks,
and for the most part was fully hedged against contracts with
their exporting clients."
</P>
<P>
As of the end of 1997, total external debt that is due in 1998
would amount to 57.7 billion ringgit or 14.4 billion U.S. dollars,
it said.
</P>
</TEXT>
