<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mountainous Parts of Southern China Getting Away From Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, March 25 (Xinhua) -- China's Guangdong Province has
one of China's seventeen poverty-stricken areas, which is trying to
eliminate poverty completely.
</P>
<P>
The mountainous area in the northern part of the province,
mainly near the city of Qingyuan, had a GDP in 1997 that was more
than three times that of a decade ago. Qingyuan now has six pillar
industries in porcelain, building materials, textiles,
electricity, foods, and tourism.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong established Qingyuan in 1988 from the poorest
counties. By using mountain agriculture, the city has developed
agriculture centers for grains, fruits, and vegetables, and had an
output that was 67.8 percent more than a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
The Qingyuan government has made an effort to develop the
mountain area by improving the investment conditions and the
opening-up policies. By 1997, it increased the length of roads by
2,728 kilometers as compared with 1987 and opened trade relations
with the United States, Japan, and European countries. Exports and
actual foreign investment in 1997 were 38.5 and 78.5 times that of
1987, respectively.
</P>
<P>
It established a poverty-relief zone that was listed by the
State Council as an experimental zone for agriculture reform. By
1997, it had 90 enterprises and eight projects, and 20 townships
established 70 projects, providing 3,000 jobs.
</P>
<P>
After four years of work, 28,000 buildings and 800 villages for
migrant workers have been built, with an average annual income per
person of 1,380 yuan in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The average GDP of Qingyuan was over 300 US dollars in
1994. Half of the million people living in poverty in Guangdong
escaped poverty by 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
