<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Development Zone in Eastern China to Help Get Rid of Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, March 25 (Xinhua) -- What was previously the poorest
county in China's Zhejiang Province, Pan'an, has found a better
life with the help of a development zone in the nearby city of
Jinhua.
</P>
<P>
This new method of poverty-eradication focuses on using local
economic potential. Pan'an is in a mountainous area without good
transportation and information services, which were impossible to
provide in the short run.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, Jinhua, its well-developed neighbor, set out to lend a
hand by giving it a two-square-kilometer piece of land to the
south of the city at a low cost. For the past two years, it has
worked with the county to build a development zone here, whose
industrial and trade revenues it controls.
</P>
<P>
The zone benefits from preferential government
policies. Investors in the zone have tax exemptions for the first
three years. Businesses mainly employ people from Pan'an and some
manufacturers have set up plants in the county to get access to
local natural resources.
</P>
<P>
Granite and Xianggu mushrooms from Pan'an do well both at home
and abroad and it has become China's largest mushroom exporter
with a quarter of the country's Xianggu exports, adding 200 yuan
per capita annually to the county.
</P>
<P>
Its per capita annual income in 1997 exceeded 1,000 yuan, well
above China's official poverty-line of 500 yuan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
