<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's GDP to Grow Slightly in 1998: Institute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Japan's real gross domestic product
(GDP) for 1998 fiscal year will inch up 0.1 percent, a private
research institute predicted Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
But the GDP for 1997 is expected to shrink 0.4 percent,
according to the institute, which is affiliated to the Nomura
Securities Co.
</P>
<P>
The forecast included an inflation-adjusted GDP growth rate of
0.5 percent for 1999.
</P>
<P>
The survey takes into consideration additional public projects
and tax cuts totalling five to six trillion yen (about 38.5 billion
to 46.2 billion U.S. dollars) in each fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
In 1998 fiscal year which is to start on April 1, Japan's
domestic demand will drop but not as severely as in fiscal 1997,
the institute said.
</P>
<P>
Japan's personal spending, which is an important force in the
economy, has been sluggish since the government raised the
consumption tax rate from three percent to five percent last
April. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
