<DOCNO> XIE19980325.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Balance of Payments to Improve in 1998: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's overall balance
of payments is expected to improve significantly in 1998 with the
current account deficit projected to narrow substantially, the
State Bank said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The current account deficit was projected at 1.4 billion
ringgit (about 386.526 million U.S. dollars) or just 0.5 percent
of gross national product (GNP) in 1998 against the deficit of
13.4 billion ringgit (about 3.699 billion U.S. dollars) or 5.1
percent of GNP in 1997, the bank said in its 1997 annual report
released here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The 1998 projection is well below the government's target of
3.0 percent, it said.
</P>
<P>
The report said a large surplus is expected in the merchandise
account, which is anticipated to increase markedly to 27.6 billion
ringgit (about 7.62 billion U.S. dollars) from 11.1 billion
ringgit (about 3.064 billion U.S. dollars) in 1997 mainly because
of a more rapid expansion in exports (36.6 percent) against
imports (30.6 percent).
</P>
<P>
The bank said adjustment measures, particularly fiscal
cutbacks, deferment of several large projects and reduction in
credit growth for less productive sectors had contributed to a
contraction in domestic demand.
</P>
<P>
These measures would result in a significant improvement in the
balance of payments position as well as greater efficiency in the
allocation of resources towards higher value-added activities, it
added.
</P>
<P>
It said that overall, the depreciation of the ringgit exerted
some positive impact on the balance of payments for 1997, which
was most evident in the-better-than expected performance of the
trade account.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's exports in 1997 amounted to 218.7 billion ringgit
(about 60.381 billion U.S. dollars at the present rate) against
193.1 billion ringgit (about 53.313 billion U.S. dollars) in 1996,
it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
