<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO Criticizes S. Africa for Failure to Curb TB </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 25 (Xinhua) -- The World Health
Organization (WHO) has been highly critical of South Africa for
losing the battle against tuberculosis (TB), The Citizen daily
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Latest estimates by South Africa's Medical Research Council
are that by the year 2005, about one percent of all South
Africans, will be infected with TB.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, more than 103,000 TB cases were registered. In 1997,
the figure rose to 160,000. In addition, 1.4 million South
Africans are infected with both TB and HIV/AIDS.
</P>
<P>
About 1,000 South Africans are killed every month by the
disease.
</P>
<P>
Following the WHO statement Tuesday, World TB Day, Democratic
Party healthcare spokesman Bukelwa Mbulawa introduced a motion in
the National Assembly calling on the government to halt the
disease.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the WHO finding that South Africa had one of the
highest rates of TB infection in the world, Mbulawa said TB
killed more South Africans than AIDS, malaria and murder
combined.
</P>
<P>
If the current trend continues, it was estimated that 3.5
million South Africans would be infected by the year 2006, many
of them incurably infected with new drug-resistant strains.
</P>
<P>
Mbulawa blamed the growing infection on failure of the
government's primary healthcare program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980325.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Experts Call for Measures to Protect Qinghai Lake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'NING, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Chinese experts warned that the
fish population in Qinghai Lake, China's largest saltwater lake,
will decline and birds will disappear if nothing is done to stop
environmental deterioration.
</P>
<P>
Experts in the Northwest Plateau Ecological Research Institute
under the Chinese Academy of Sciences have called for immediate
measures to protect Qinghai Lake from further pollution, which is
a key point for the ecological balance of the Qinghai-Tibet
Plateau.
</P>
<P>
Located in the northeastern part of the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau,
the lake abounds in huso sturgeon, a rare species of fish, and
rare birds that co-exist peacefully with the fish.
</P>
<P>
However, the lake is drying up and grassland around it is in
danger of desertification, which could lead to great natural
disasters, they said.
</P>
<P>
"Over-grazing of livestock is one of the most important factors
that lead to desertification of grassland," said Chen Guichen,
an associate researcher in the institute.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics, the lake can feed at most 1.94 million
livestock, but the number of animals in the lake area now exceeds
three million.
</P>
<P>
Overuse of the lake water for agricultural purposes in recent
years has also caused an oversupply of water drained from the
lake. The lake's water level has been dropping an average of 10
centimeters a year since 1959, Chen said.
</P>
<P>
Strong winds and moving dunes frequently destroy birds' nests
and food supply. The coverage of desert areas has reportedly
increased to 700 square kilometers.
</P>
<P>
Birds living on the island in the middle of the lake have also
been endangered because of appearance of large numbers of animals
there.
</P>
<P>
Chen said that deteriorating environment of the lake will turn
out to be a great danger to the ecosystem of the Qinghai-Tibet
Plateau. He suggested that the Chinese government take measures
to protect the lake. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
