<DOCNO> XIE19980325.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EC Recommends 11 member States for Single Currency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 25 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission has
recommended 11 European Union countries for the single currency to
be launched in January 1999.
</P>
<P>
The recommendation was made on Wednesday during a special
hearing of the European Parliament, to which the commission, the
executive agency of the 15-nation union, presented its report on
European Monetary Union convergence.
</P>
<P>
Belgium, Germany, Spain, France, Ireland, Italy, Luxembourg,
the Netherlands, Austria, Portugal and Finland were recommended as
having met the conditions to adopt the single currency, the Euro.
</P>
<P>
To qualify for the final stage of EMU, member states must
attain a high degree of sustainable economic convergence.
</P>
<P>
Progress is measured against criteria covering inflation,
government deficit and debt, exchange rate stability and long-term
interest rates.
</P>
<P>
EU member states must also meet certain other conditions such
as central bank independence.
</P>
<P>
The commission has already adopted the recommendation of the 11
member states on the initiative of Commission President Jacques
Santer and Commissioner Yves-Thibault de Silguy responsible for
economic, monetary and financial affairs.
</P>
<P>
It recommended that these 11 countries be the founder members
of EMU from January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The EU heads of state and government will confirm the list of
the first-wave EMU countries at a summit meeting on May 2.
</P>
<P>
The confirmation will be made on the basis of the commission's
recommendation and its convergence report together with another
convergence report prepared by the European Monetary Institute.
</P>
<P>
The final decision will be taken on a recommendation from the
EU economy and finance ministers council meeting after consulting
the European Parliament.
</P>
<P>
If the 11 recommended countries are confirmed by the EU summit,
this will create a Euro-zone with nearly 300 million inhabitants
accounting for 19.4 percent of world gross domestic product (GDP)
and 18.6 percent of world trade.
</P>
<P>
This compares with 19.6 percent of world GDP and 16.6 percent
of world trade for the United States and 7.7 percent of world GDP
and 8.2 percent of world trade for Japan.
</P>
<P>
Britain, the current holder of the rotating EU presidency, and
Denmark exercised their right under the Maastricht Treaty and
opted out of the first wave for EMU. Greece and Sweden were judged
by the commission not economically ready to join for the time
being. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
