<HEADLINE> Thailand Seeks Guarantees for ASEAN Exporters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 25 (Xinhua) -- A Thai Foreign Ministry official
on Wednesday confirmed a newspaper report that Thailand would ask
Singapore to help set up a multilateral forum to secure guarantees
for all ASEAN exporters.
</P>
<P>
Today's Bangkok Post reported that Thai Prime Minister Chuan
Leekpai would stress to his Singaporean counterpart Goh Chok Tong,
who arrives here today for a 24-hour visit, that Singapore should
not seek export guarantees for Indonesia only.
</P>
<P>
Goh called on the international community to set up a
multilateral forum to help Indonesian exporters when he visited
the country last month.
</P>
<P>
The officials said all ASEAN exporters, not just only those in
Indonesia, have been beset by problems of obtaining letters of
credit.
</P>
<P>
Thailand wants all ASEAN members to jointly lobby European and
U.S. support for the forum, the official said on condition of
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
Chuan and Goh are expected to discuss preparation for the
Asian-European Summit due to take place in London in early April.
Other topics of discussion are likely to include Asia's position
in the region's financial crisis and Malaysia's proposal for using
local currencies to replace the U.S. dollar in trade among ASEAN
members.
</P>
<P>
Asian leaders will push for a statement at the summit which
would urge other nations to do more to address the regional
currency crisis, said the Thai Foreign Ministry official.
</P>
<P>
He said Thailand would also want the statement to call on
developed countries to make efforts to help restore confidence in
the region and to open up their markets and provide bank and
credit facilities to the crisis-hit countries as well. 
</P>
