<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Textile Reform Proceeding Steadily, Officials Say (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 25 (Xinhua) -- China's central and local
governments are united and determined in their efforts to
reinvigorate the textile industry through restructuring, according
to government officials.
</P>
<P>
In a recent meeting with Ye Rongbao, deputy-governor of east
China's Zhejiang Province, the vice-chairman of China National
Textile Council (CNTC), Xu Kunyuan, said that reducing the number
of cotton spindles and stopping losses of state-owned cotton mills
will be the final opportunity that the textile industry has before
the end of the century.
</P>
<P>
"The textile enterprises have no way out but restructuring,"
said Xu.
</P>
<P>
State-owned textile enterprises have become the largest
unprofitable group among other industries. These enterprises have
more employees than any other state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The central government has decided to make the textile industry
an area of breakthroughs in restructuring medium- and large-scale
state-owned enterprises this year.
</P>
<P>
The move is designed to transform the industry from red to
black in three years. The government has drafted a series of
policies in this process.
</P>
<P>
Ye said that the central government's policies have added
impetus to Zhejiang Province's drive to restructure the local
economy.
</P>
<P>
She said the local economy is at the transitional stage from
medium-developed to developed. The province has taken pains to
scale down outdated cotton-spinning in the past few years.
</P>
<P>
Even before the central government released relevant policies,
the province had already reduced the number of spindles at cotton
mills by 230,000.
</P>
<P>
Ye said the province will slash the number of cotton spindles
by another 430,000 in the next two years, one year ahead of the
schedule set by the central government.
</P>
<P>
Xu said that the destruction of spindles is aimed to get rid of
excessive production capacity by outdated cotton mills. Through
restructuring, down-sizing employees and reducing debt, most of
the medium- and large-size state-owned cotton textile enterprises
will shake off the doldrums and become vigorous in market
competition, Xu said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that in an ever-changing market, heads of
state-owned enterprises should take the lead to change concepts
and ideology. They should learn about new products, technology and
trends in the international textile market, Ye said, so that they
can steer the enterprises toward expansion in intense
competition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
