<DOCNO> XIE19980325.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese, U.S. Senior Judges Meet in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Justice Ma Yuan, vice-president
of the China Judges Association, met here today with Dorothy
Nelson, senior judge of the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, to
discuss the judicial systems of both countries.
</P>
<P>
Ma briefed Nelson on the establishment of China's judicial system
in the last two decades, especially the implementation of
China's new criminal code which was passed last year.
</P>
<P>
The articles in the new criminal code have been increased to
452 from 192, Ma said.
</P>
<P>
The code has also explicitly stipulated the principle of "not
guilty unless proven under the law" to avoid the biases of judges
in the conviction and punishment phases, Ma said.
</P>
<P>
The new code has also emphasized citizens' "right of a just
defense" to more effectively protect the legitimate rights and
interests of the state, society and its citizens, Ma said.
</P>
<P>
Nelson told Ma that many people in the United States are
concerned about the development of China's judicial system and the
implementation of the country's new criminal code. She said that
the adoption of the principle of "not guilty unless proven under
the law" in the new code is a sign of progress in China's legal
system.
</P>
<P>
She said the U.S. criminal code also needs improvement and the
two countries could learn from each other.
</P>
<P>
In response to a question about "interference" from government
institutions or other departments, Ma said the independence of
China's judiciary is explicitly stipulated in the law.
</P>
<P>
However, China is still working toward the goal of "rule by
law" and it is hard for the judicial departments to be totally free
from outside interference or influence in law enforcement, Ma told
Nelson. But the absolute majority of Chinese judges can overcome
outside interference and enforce the law fairly, she said.
</P>
<P>
Nelson was appointed to the bench by President Jimmy Carter in
1979. She was dean of the University of Southern California Law
Center, where she had been a professor since 1957.
</P>
<P>
Nelson's current China trip, sponsored by the Chinese People's
Association for Friendship with Foreign Countries, will also take
her to Hangzhou in east China's Zhejiang Province and Kunming in
southwest China's Yunnan Province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
