<HEADLINE> Nigeria Woos Investment to Upgrade Telecom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian Communications Minister
Patrick Aziza has said that his country is seeking six
billion U.S. dollars to improve its telecommunication facilities.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the three-day seminar tagged "Nigeria Telecom
'98 ", which opened on Tuesday in Abuja, Aziza said that at least
six billion U.S. dollars is needed to "meet our immediate
requirements of over three million telephone lines and 200,000
cellular lines."
</P>
<P>
Besides, the nation's telecommunications industry would
require about 600 million dollars a year for network expansion,
he added.
</P>
<P>
According to Aziza, the current telephone density in Nigeria
stands at one line to 200 people, which is far below the one line
to 100 people standard prescribed by the International
Telecommunications Union.
</P>
<P>
Under the country's first long-term socio-economic development
program, "Vision 2010", a target of approximately eight million
lines should be installed by the year 2010, based on an average
growth rate of 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
Admitting that the financial burden cannot be borne by the
government alone, the minister called on the organized private
sector and foreign investors to invest in the industry.
</P>
<P>
"The government expects that the combination of the resources
of government and private operators will provide the desired
investment level to accelerate telecommunications network
expansion which will then enable the government to withdraw and
allow the private sector to take the driver's seat to achieve
sustainable telecommunications development," said Aziza.
</P>
<P>
As the sector is being opened up for both domestic and foreign
investments, the emerging telecommunication environment will
offer a range of new opportunities for the investors, said the
minister.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
