<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Financial Crisis in East Asia Can Affect World Trade: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, March 25 (Xinhua) -- The financial crisis
experienced by East Asian countries is expected to affect growth
in the world output and trade this year, Malaysia's State Bank
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The impact of the crisis on the major industrial economies
would vary, depending on their exposure to trade and investment in
the region, the central bank said in its 1997 annual report
released here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The bank said the East Asian crisis was unprecedented in terms
of degree and extent and that due to the region's increasing
importance and integration with the global economy and
international financial markets, the negative impact of the
turmoil was expected to reach beyond regional boundaries.
</P>
<P>
"Uncertainty remains with regards to the duration and the
spread of the crisis, which could eventually alter the world
economic and financial environment, and thus the short to medium
term outlook for the world economy," it pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Eventually, there was a spillover of the regional crisis onto
the world financial markets, when it generated a global stock
market decline in late October last year, and had since
contributed to continued volatility in most equity markets, it
added.
</P>
<P>
The bank, however, said the region's economies would be most
affected by the crisis as the prolonged uncertainty and
implementation of strong measures and structural changes to
overcome present macroeconomic imbalances took effect.
</P>
<P>
"In the short term, fiscal tightening and monetary restraint,
and the restructuring of the economy and the corporate and
financial sectors, can be expected to exert a dampening influence
on growth prospects. However, these measures would pave the way
for a more sustainable and broad-based growth over the medium
term," it said.
</P>
<P>
The significant adjustment of a country currency's was almost
instantly followed by some adjustments in the other regional
currencies, and the pressures on the currencies and equity markets
reinforced each other, it added.
</P>
<P>
The depreciation of the domestic currency led to sharp falls in
shares prices while the consequent capital outflows exerted
further the pressure on the exchange rate, it said.
</P>
<P>
The crisis also triggered a loss of confidence in the financial
system and reflected the excesses of the private sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980325.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China: Economic, Social, Cultural Rights to Be Stressed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, March 25 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese delegate Wednesday
called on the Commission of Human Rights to give more attention to
economic, social and cultural rights.
</P>
<P>
Wu Jianmin, head of the Chinese delegation, told the 54th
session of the U.N. Human Rights Commission that only 33 out of
the 534 resolutions passed by the Commission since 1992 deal with
economic, social and cultural rights.
</P>
<P>
The figures illustrated that those rights and the right to
development had not been given adequate attention, Wu said.
</P>
<P>
In the 1990s, while voices calling for the promotion and
protection of human rights were growing louder worldwide, Official
Development Assistance (ODA) had kept on declining, Wu added.
</P>
<P>
By 1996, he noted, the ODA fell to its lowest point since 1973,
accounting for 0.27 percent of the Gross Domestic Product of the
developed countries, far below the 0.7 percent U.N. requirement.
</P>
<P>
The figures exposed a serious imbalance in the work of the
Commission, resulting from the tendency to over-emphasize civil
and political rights to the neglect of economic, social and
cultural rights and the right to development, he said.
</P>
<P>
Wu went on to point out that 4.9 billion of the world's 5.7
billion population lived in developing countries.
</P>
<P>
"However important civil and political rights may be, the
primary concern of the 4.9 billion people is about the realization
of their economic, social and cultural rights as well as the right
to development," he added.
</P>
<P>
"If the United Nations failed to pay enough attention to their
concern, it would find itself estranged from the majority of the
world's population," he cautioned. "Consequently, mainstreaming
human rights in the UN could hardly succeed." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
