<HEADLINE> World Bank to Call Special Meeting on Indonesia: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"The meeting will provide an opportunity to present assessments
of the humanitarian impact of the current economic crisis and
severe drought," Downer was quoted by the Australian Associated
Press as saying.
</P>
<P>
"Most importantly, the meeting will facilitate coordination of
international assistance for Indonesia."
</P>
<P>
Downer said the move followed his meeting in Washington
recently with World Bank President James Wolfensohn, at which he
raised Australia's concerns about the effect of the Asian economic
crisis on Indonesia's ability to feed its population.
</P>
<P>
"The combined effect of the economic crisis and the prolonged
drought have given rise to a clear danger of major food security
problems as food affordability decreases and crop harvests are
reduced."
</P>
<P>
The concerns over Indonesia was also voiced Wednesday night by
former prime minister Paul Keating in a lecture to a university in
Sydney.
</P>
<P>
Australia could not, and should not, try to insulate itself
from the 200 million people in Indonesia who were its nearest
Asian neighbors, Keating said, calling Indonesia the country of
"greatest immediate concern" to Australia.
</P>
<P>
"We stand with Indonesia" and that should be the basis of
Australian policy throughout Asia's financial crisis, the former
prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
Australia has been lobbying on Indonesia's behalf to have the
conditions of its International Monetary Fund (IMF) bailout eased
because of fears the tough economic measures demanded could lead
to food shortages and social upheaval.
</P>
<P>
Australia has contributed one billion U.S. dollars to the IMF's
43 billion U.S. dollar bailout of Indonesia, as well as donating
5.8 million U.S. dollars for drought and up to 254 million U.S.
dollars in insurance cover for wheat sales.
</P>
<P>
Australian armed forces have made emergency plans to evacuate
Australians in Indonesia in case turmoil develops in the country,
Australian newspapers reported earlier this month. 
</P>
