<HEADLINE> Malaysian Economy to Recover in 1998: State Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's economy is
expected to recover from the full impact of the current economic
crisis in the second half of 1998, Malaysian State Bank said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"The full impact of the crisis on the domestic economy is
expected to be felt in the first half of this year," the central
bank said in its 1997 annual report released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Gross domestic product growth would slow down to between two
and three percent in 1998 after a decade of rapid growth, it said,
adding notwithstanding the slowdown in growth and some increase
in unemployment, the economy would remain positive in the first
half of this year, with stronger growth taking place in the second
half of 1998.
</P>
<P>
It said "This projection is premised on prospective
developments in the international and regional environment, as
well as developments in the domestic economy in the context of the
government's macroeconomic adjustment program."
</P>
<P>
The implementation of the adjustment measures, introduced in
December 1997, as well as emerging signs of restoration of
regional financial stability have had a positive effect in
restoring investor confidence, it said.
</P>
<P>
Other positive developments have been the
stronger-than-projected exports of 218.7 billion ringgit (60.381
billion U.S. dollars at the present rate) in 1997, against 193.1
billion ringgit (53.313 billion U.S. dollars) in 1996, and some
recovery in the equity market, it added.
</P>
<P>
The bank said "Should this trend strengthen, the prospects for
growth could be higher."
</P>
<P>
However, it pointed out that a number of risks remained and
they included a sharper-than-expected moderation in world growth
and trade, a more prolonged regional crisis and the uncertain
outlook for exports of electronic and electrical goods, the major
export items of Malaysia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
