<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korea Bettering Trade with Industrialized Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, March 25 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's trade deficit with
industrialized countries has either been wiped out or reduced
considerably, said the Commerce, Industry, and Energy Ministry
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The first two months of this year saw that industrialized
nations, such as France, the United States and Canada, no longer
enjoyed a trade surplus with South Korea while the nation's trade
deficit with Japan dropped, said an analysis report by the
ministry.
</P>
<P>
South Korea's trade surplus with the United States amounted to
219 million U.S. dollars in the first two months of this year
while it also enjoyed a surplus of 39 million U.S. dollar with
France, two million dollars with Canada.
</P>
<P>
The nation's trade deficit with the United States stood at 8.36
billion U.S. dollars last year, the second largest only next to
its deficit of 13.65 billion U.S. dollar with Japan.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, South Korea's deficit with European countries turned
into a surplus totaling 740 million U.S. dollars from last year's
deficit of 2.07 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The country's deficit with Japan plummeted to 554 million
dollars in the past two months from 2.25 billion in the same
period of 1997.
</P>
<P>
South Korea's improved trade balance came from the country's
expanded exports, decreased imports, and sharp devaluation of the
won in the past months since it signed an agreement with the
International Monetary Fund last December for a rescue loan of 57
billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Last year witnessed the per capital income of South Korea down
to 9,400 U.S. dollars from the previous year's 10,548 U.S. dollars
due to a financial crisis triggered by corporate bankruptcies and
bad loans of financial institutions in late 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
