<HEADLINE> Tanzania Pays Membership Fee Owed to SADC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 25 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzanian government
has paid 400,000 US dollars owed to the South Africa Development
Community (SADC) as membership fee.
</P>
<P>
The amount of money was paid following the 12-nation
organization threatened to suspend Tanzania's membership at a
summit in Mozambique last year because the country has failed to
pay annual fees for three years, Dar es Salaam newspapers said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Tanzanian government, though facing economic difficulties,
recently paid the fee so as to maintain its rights as an active
member of the community, foreign ministry sources said.
</P>
<P>
All SADC member countries with huge debts will not be allowed
to vote, speak out or give any opinions or suggestions to any
matter dealing with the community when attending the next SADC
summit in September this year.
</P>
<P>
SADC, headquartered in Gaberone, capital of Botswana, is
committed to break tariff barriers and promote trade and
investment in order to realize economic integration within the
south African region.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, SADC plans to launch a regional electoral
monitoring group which will ensure that elections held in member
states are free and fair in a move to push forward the region's
democratic process, said seasoned diplomat ambassador Ahamed
Hassan Diria who has just returned from a SADC meeting in
Botswana held last week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
