<HEADLINE> Large Amount of Sulphur Ore Found in Southeastern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, March 25 (Xinhua) -- An exceptionally large sulphur
ore deposit, reportedly China's largest, amounting to more than 10
billion tons, was verified recently in Guizhou Province in
southwestern China.
</P>
<P>
The sulphur ore is scattered over a 2,570-sq.km. area, mainly
in Dafang County, and contains an average 15 percent of sulphur,
fit for sulphuric acid production, specialists say.
</P>
<P>
Experts anticipate that the fine sulphur ore supply will fall
short of the growing market demand with the development of the
sulphuric acid industry. Guizhou needs
1.3 million tons of sulphur ore for 1998, but there are less than
200,000 tons of supplies.
</P>
<P>
The province is planning an 800,000-ton sulphur ore base
and two more 300,000-ton sulphur ore dressing areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
