<HEADLINE> U.S. not to Dictate Political Systems on Others, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 25 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. will not dictate any
political system on a sovereignty, the U.S. special envoy for
democratization in Africa told Ugandan multipartists Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time a U.S. diplomat commented publicly on
multipartism.
</P>
<P>
Reverend Jesse Jackson said the U.S. has no right to prescribe
political systems for other sovereign countries at a luncheon
organized by Michael Mckinley, the U.S. Deputy Ambassador to the
country, for Uganda and visiting U.S. political figures in
Kampala.
</P>
<P>
Uganda insists repeatedly multipartism applies no conditions
in Uganda. Multipartism only causes tribalism and chaos in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Uganda has various political groups. But Ugandan authorities
hold that these groups are not the real political parties.
</P>
<P>
According to The New Vision Wednesday, guests of Tuesday's
party were Paul Semogerere, the leader of democratic party,
Mayanja Nkangi, the leader of conservative party, Muhammad
Mayanja, the leader of Forum Party, Cecilia Ogwal and James
Rwanyarare, the leaders of Uganda People's Party, Joe Oloka
Onyago, the leader of peace center, among others.
</P>
<P>
Uganda multipartists asked to meet Bill Clinton, the visiting
U.S. president, before his arrival in the country.
</P>
<P>
Clinton arrived in the country early Tuesday and is to leave the
country late Wednesday. 
</P>
