<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Families Spend 50 U.S. Dollars Per Month </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian families spent an average
of 4,058 Naira (about 50 U.S. dollars) per month each in 1997,
the Federal Office of Statistics said in a recent survey.
</P>
<P>
The office said in its report "National Consumer Survey,
1996/97" that rural families spent an average of 3,755 Naira
(about 47 U.S. dollars) per month each, while the figure for
urban families is 5,166 Naira (about 65 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
"Expenditure in the north-west zone had the least figure of
2,941 Naira (about 37 U.S. dollars), while in the south-eastern
zone 5,194 Naira (about 65 U.S. dollars), almost double the
figure for the north-west zone," the report said.
</P>
<P>
The average household income in Nigeria was 5,383 Naira (about
67 U.S. dollars) per month, representing 6,490 Naira (about 81
U.S. dollars) in urban centers and 5,000 Naira (about 63 U.S.
dollars) in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
The per capita income for Nigerians was 1,460 Naira (about 18
U.S. dollars) in the urban areas, and 1,054 Naira (about 13 U.S.
dollars) in the rural areas, showing a difference of 39 percent.
</P>
<P>
The report set the poverty level at 658 Naira (about eight
U.S. dollars), which produced an impoverished population of 43
percent in urban areas and 50 percent in rural areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
