<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's Interim Budget Presented to Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Indian Finance Minister
Yashwant Sinha Wednesday presented to the Parliament the
government's interim budget for 1998-99 (April 1,1998-March 31,
1999) to enable the government to carry on its business.
</P>
<P>
India's annual budget is usually presented to the Parliament
every February. As the change of government which was formulated
on March 19, an interim budget as a vote-on-account has to be
presented so as to meet essential expenditure during the first
four months of the next financial year. The regular budget for
1998-99 is expected to be ready in a few weeks time.
</P>
<P>
In his speech to the Parliament here, Yashwant Sinha said that
the overall economic growth has slowed to five percent in 1997-98,
agriculture has registered negative growth of two percent,
industry continues to be in the doldrums averaging only 4.6
percent growth over the 12 months up to January 1998, and exports
have recorded negative growth in U.S. dollar terms in each of the
three most recent months up to January 1998.
</P>
<P>
The total expenditure in 1998-99 is estimated at 2,649,880
million rupees (68.83 billion U.S. dollars) as against 2,352,450
million rupees (61.10 billion U.S. dollars) in the current year.
No-plan expenditure in 1998-99 is estimated to be 2,005,270
million rupees (52.08 billion U.S. dollars) against 1,746,150
million rupees (45.36 billion U.S. dollars) in the current year,
the finance minister said.
</P>
<P>
The total non-debt receipts including tax revenues at existing
rates of taxation, are estimated at 1,681,730 million rupees
(43.68 billion U.S. dollars). The fiscal deficit for 1998-99 will
be about 6 percent of GDP, he said. The targeted fiscal deficit
was pegged at 4.5 percent of GDP. 
</P>
</TEXT>
