<HEADLINE> Cote d'Ivoire Flays U.S.: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Ivorien Foreign Minister Essy
Amara has described a statement recently credited to the United
States on the political situation in Nigeria as an insult not
only to Nigerians but to all Africans.
</P>
<P>
Africans "are mature enough to fashion out their own
destines," he said, quoted by the official newspaper New Nigerian
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Amara was in Nigeria to deliver a solidarity message from
President Henri Konan Bedie to Nigerian Head of State General
Sani Abacha.
</P>
<P>
The Ivorien minister expressed regret that the U.S. had chosen
to ignore Nigeria's credible historic achievements in
peacekeeping all over the world in preference to less-significant
issues.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the restoration of peace and democracy in
Liberia and Sierra Loene to the sterling leadership of General
Abacha as the current chairman of the Economic Community of West
African States (ECOWAS).
</P>
<P>
According to him, the message from Presidnt Bedie was
necessitated by the comments credited to U.S. assistant Secretary
of State for Foreign Affairs Susan Rice who recently called "the
military dictatorship in Nigeria one of the worst abusers of
human rights on the continent".
</P>
<P>
While urging General Abacha to undertake a "genuine
transition", Rice stated "an electoral victory by any military
candidate in the forthcoming presidential election would be
unacceptable".
</P>
<P>
This statement, Amara noted, was "a flagrant interference in
the internal affairs of Nigeria".
</P>
<P>
Responding, General Abacha urged all nations to learn to
respect the sovereignty and independence of others in the
interest of harmonious international relations.  
</P>
</TEXT>
