<HEADLINE> UN Aircraft Attacked in Angola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Two helicopters of the United
Nations inspection mission were shot by the "military remnants"
of the former rebel force in northern Angola's Malanje Province.
</P>
<P>
It is reported by local media Wednesday that the two Mig-eight
helicopters were shot by the military men of the National Union
for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) when they were
landing in Camdundi-Catembo area.
</P>
<P>
Camdundi-Catembo area is still under the control of UNITA.
</P>
<P>
The helicopters were forced to return to Malanje City, capital
of the province by the same name after the attack.
</P>
<P>
The UN representatives, government officials and UNITA leaders
on board the helicopters for a re-establishement ceremony of
government organ there were forced back, luckily unhurt.
</P>
<P>
The effort to re-open government institutions there have been
hampered three times. On February 18, a UN inspection mission
helicopter was also forced back after being shot by UNITA
military men at the same place.
</P>
<P>
UNITA representatives to Malanje admitted Tuesday that the
attackers were its men.  
</P>
