<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Contact Group Mulls Solutions to Kosovo Conflict </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Foreign ministers of the six-nation
Contact Group met here Wednesday in a bid to find new approaches
to end the conflict in the southern Serbian province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
According to diplomatic sources in Bonn, the meeting has a main
objective to urge the federal Yugoslav leadership, not just
Serbia, to begin a political dialogue with Kosovo Albanians on the
future status of the region.
</P>
<P>
However, the talks have been overshadowed by difference in
opinions among the Contact Group members consisting of Britain,
France, Germany, Italy, Russia and the United States.
</P>
<P>
While U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright proposes to
tighten sanctions on Belgrade, most other group members is said to
favor "maintaining pressure" on Belgrade to enter talks.
</P>
<P>
Although some economic and diplomatic sanctions were already
decided at the Contact Group's last meeting in London on March 9,
Russia disagrees to go ahead with them for reasons that Belgrade
has already made some progress to meet the demands raised by the
London meeting.
</P>
<P>
On the eve of the Bonn meeting, Albright and her Russian
counterpart Yevgeni Primakov met in Cologne Tuesday evening trying
to iron out their differences.
</P>
<P>
German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel also held separate talks with
Albright and Primakov earlier Wednesday to prepare for the group's
meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Contact Group is also due to hold consultations on the same
day in Bonn with foreign ministers from eight nations in the
neighborhood of Yugoslavia to discuss how to maintain stability in
the entire region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
