<DOCNO> XIE19980325.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Launch Large Environmental Protection Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, March 25 (Xinhua) -- China will invest more than six
billion yuan (750 million U.S. dollars) in launching a large
project to improve the environment in the source regions of the
Yellow and Yangtze rivers, the two longest in China.
</P>
<P>
The comprehensive treatment project will cover an area of
326,000 square kilometers, which includes five autonomous
prefectures of ethnic groups and 34 counties in northwest China's
Qinghai Province.
</P>
<P>
"It will take 13 years to complete the project if it is
launched this year as scheduled," said a leading official with the
Qinghai Provincial agriculture and forestry department, a major
partner in the project.
</P>
<P>
The project will concentrate on planting forests, preventing
soil erosion and fighting desertification, the official said.
</P>
<P>
The source regions of the Yellow and Yangtze rivers have an
elevation of more than 4,000 meters and are plagued with severe
cold and dry weather, prominent features of the local natural
environment. Destruction of the region's forests and grasslands
have led to soil erosion and desertification, which has posed a
threat to the local ecology.
</P>
<P>
"The investment will be funneled to the project in two stages
with financial support from the central government," said Wang
Qian, director of the provincial forestry bureau. The project will
provide comprehensive management and protection of the environment
of seven river valleys. Shelter greenbelts will be planted in the
source regions of the two rivers.
</P>
<P>
Efforts have been made by the local government to protect the
environment in the source regions in recent years, where forests
cover 208,000 hectares with 93 million trees planted.
</P>
<P>
After the project's completion, the forest coverage rate of the
source region is expected to rise to 10.42 percent from current
4.87 percent, according to an analysis by the provincial forestry
department. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
