<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Rise on Singapore Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Boosted by a rise in demand for
penny stocks by retail buyers amid thin interest for blue chips,
share prices rose on the Singapore market as the benchmark Straits
Times Industrials Index (STII) surged by 26.68 points to close at
1667.22 points on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that institutions were mostly sidelined on a lack
of market-moving factors as they wound down business ahead of the
end of the fiscal year next week. In addition, anticipation of
rate cuts by major banks helped boost the market sentiment, they
said.
</P>
<P>
The total market volume increased marginally to 367.4 million
units, valued at 335.69 million Singapore dollars (about 209.81
million U.S. dollars). Advances overwhelmed declines by 344 to 66,
while 201 other counters remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Easyknit was the most actively traded stock as it registered a
turnover of 31.13 million units. It was followed by IPC
Corporation which had 24.49 million shares traded. MBf Capital was
next with 18.66 million shares changed hands.
</P>
<P>
Creative 200 led the gainers of the day as it rose by 80 cents
to finish at 35.7 Singapore dollars. Bukit Sembawang increased by
70 cents to end at 11.8 Singapore dollars. Local car distributor
Cycle &AMP; Carriage (C&AMP;C) was up by 35 cents to close at 7.65
Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, Hiap Moh was the biggest loser as it declined
by 24.5 cents to end at 70 Singapore cents. SIA (Singapore
Airlines) Foreign fell by 20 cents to close at 11.7 Singapore
dollars, while Boustd S was down by 17 cents to finish at 1.73
Singapore dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
