<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 25 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading French newspapers Wednesday:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- The political bureau of the Union for French Democracy (UDF)
 Tuesday urged the resignation of five members of the party who
were elected presidents of regional councils with the votes of
far-right National Front, or face expulsion from the party. The
leader of the Liberal Democratic Party, a splinter party of UDF,
Alain Madelin, did not join this appeal for resignation.
</P>
<P>
-- U.S. President Bill Clinton Tuesday apologized in Uganda for
the black slave trade by Europeans in history and described
slavery as "the biggest sin of America." He also apologized for
the ignorance of Americans about Africa until now.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- In an interview with the Russian private television NTV, the
new prime minister appointed by Yeltsin, Sergey Kiriyenko,
presented himself as an enterprise manager far from political
intrigues.
</P>
<P>
-- Commenting on the on-going visit to Africa by U.S. President
Bill Clinton, Jacques Godfrain, former French minister of
cooperation, said that the visit by Clinton means Africa is no
longer a drifting away continent but a place where one can make
money. But he deplored the ultra-liberal "trade not aid" policy
of the United States toward Africa, which he said could be used
as an excuse for selective embargo on countries such as Sudan and
Libya. 
</P>
</TEXT>
