<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fisherman Releases Captured Sea Turtle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Fisherman Wang Mutang is feeling
great that he was able to return a 100-year-old sea turtle to sea,
even though some of his friends are sorry that he lost a chance to
make money.
</P>
<P>
The turtle -- 1.9 meters long, 1.1 meters wide, and weighing
more than 250 kilograms -- was captured by Wang on March 9, while
deep-sea fishing.
</P>
<P>
People around him were delighted with the news, believing it
was a good chance for him to make a fortune. Some buyers had
contacted him with an offer as high as 4,000 yuan (481.92
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
However, upon learning that the turtle is a rare species under
second-grade national protection which rarely survives life in
captivity, Wang made an immediate decision to set it free. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980325.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 09:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Curbing Illicit Drug Trade in Lebanon Called for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, March 25 (Xinhua) -- A parliament member has warned
that illegal trade in medicine has soared to a level in lebanon
that it is endangering people's lives, the Daily Star newspaper
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
At a news conference Tuesday, Ismail Sukkarieh said that
staying silent about what is happening in the pharmaceutical
market is a crime, and helping criminal pill salesmen is an even
bigger crime.
</P>
<P>
"We are raising this huge and dangerous issue because it
concerns everybody, not one group and not another," Sukkarieh said.
</P>
<P>
He added that nothing is being done to stop drugs well past
their expiration date being sold on the market, which is the
reason behind many unexplained deaths.
</P>
<P>
He also blamed unscientific advertising and promotion of
unnecessary medicine and illegal distribution for "upsetting an
otherwise very professional pharmaceutical industry."
</P>
<P>
The Pharmaceutical Consultation Bureau (PCB) said in a
statement that Lebanon imported 5,968 products at a cost of 362
million U.S. dollars in 1997, 3,188 of which are not needed with a
value of 230 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The PCB said 887 brands were not registered with the technical
committee; of those 86 were sold illegally and 42 were not
registered even in the country of origin but appeared prepared
especially for export to Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon is the third largest regional consumer of medicine
after Saudi Arabia and Egypt. There are 16 chief importers and 80
companies in the country which sell medicines via 2,100
pharmacies, 164 private hospitals, 27 public hospitals, 55
government clinics and 320 private clinics.
</P>
<P>
Sukkarieh recommended that to curb the crimes, a system be set
up to register and examine imports according to international
standards, such as those of the World Health Organization (WHO),
and an up-to-date national policy.
</P>
<P>
It is also necessary to appoint a well-trained technical team
in collaboration with the WHO to run the medical sector and
implement the by-laws of the national medicine office, which will
identify a list of basic medicines, relying on those products
manufactured by international companies with research centers, he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
