<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bright Futures Market Sees Australian Stocks Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 25 (Xinhua) -- The imminent expiry of quarterly
 equity options led to changes in institutional positions
Wednesday, causing falls in major stocks on the Australian share
market.
</P>
<P>
The All Ordinaries Index fell 10.4 points to 2781.6 in mixed
trade heavily influenced by arbitraging with the futures market.
</P>
<P>
"There has been a lot of arbitraging between the futures market
and the All Ords (ordinaries)," Steve Negrine, a stock exchange
expert, said.
</P>
<P>
Arbitrage involves taking a position to take advantage of
pricing differences between different markets.
</P>
<P>
The All Industrials Index slid 21.6 points to 4782.3 in busy
position taking and profiteering after recent strong rises in some
stocks.
</P>
<P>
Telecommunications giant Telstra installment receipts lost
ground with a 7-cent fall to 3.87 Australian dollars after
touching new highs earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
Among the banks, Westpac was Wednesday's biggest mover with a
28-cent decline to 10.35 Australian dollars with more than 9.6
million shares traded worth 66.87 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
National Australia Bank rose 9.9 cents to 21.862 Australian
dollars, Commonwealth bank just one-tenth of a cent to 18.401
Australian dollars and ANZ bank 2 cents to 10.3 Australian
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The All Resources Index shed one point to 1183.6.
</P>
<P>
Resources giant BHP rose 3 cents to 15.918 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index rose 1.6 points to 1138.8 as the bullion price
improved again, up 1.25 U.S. dollars per ounce to 298.5 dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 358.3 million shares worth 710.8 million
U.S. dollars, with falls outnumbering rises 616 to 541. 
</P>
</TEXT>
