<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Strong Quake Hits Antarctica: AAP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 25 (Xinhua) -- A strong earthquake measured
eight on the Richter scale was Wednesday recorded off the coast of
Australia's Antarctic Territory, the Australian Associated Press
(AAP) reported.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Geological Survey Organization said the quake
happened at 14:11 Australian eastern daylight time just off the
Balleny Islands.
</P>
<P>
It came half an hour after an earthquake in the Banda Sea in
Indonesia shook Darwin, a coastal city in northern Australia,
early Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
No casualties were reported as there is nobody in the two
quake-stricken areas.
</P>
<P>
"This is a once in the world once in a year earthquake, so it's
quite a large earthquake," Kevin McCue, a seismologist at the
survey organization was quoted by AAP as saying.
</P>
<P>
"And this is the largest in the world so far this year but we
don't expect there have been any damage because there is nobody
there."
</P>
<P>
McCue said the earthquake, which shook Darwin, registered six
on the Richter scale and occurred at 13:44 Australian eastern
daylight time, north of Timor in the Banda sea.
</P>
<P>
It was "too small to have done any damage or cause a tsunami
(tidal wave), but it was felt by quite a few people in Darwin," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
