<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya's Tea Prices Fall on High Supply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan tea prices continued
their gentle decline at the weekly tea auction in Mombasa on
growing supply, the East African Standard newspaper reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A record 6.7 million kilograms of tea was sold at this week's
auction, compared to just about six million kilograms sold last
week, auction officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"We're experiencing a boom in supply at the moment. This is
the highest quantity sold at any single auction," one official
said.
</P>
<P>
"In January we sold 31.3 million kgs, the highest all time
crop, and we expect February's crop will be as good," the
official added.
</P>
<P>
Brighter and Medium BP1s were easier while Lighter Mediums
shed four-12 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
There was good buying interest from Pakistan, Britain and
Egypt, according to the report. Kenya is one of the largest tea
exporters in the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
