<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Green Shelterbelt Built to Stop Yellow River Flooding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, March 25 (Xinhua) -- A 500-kilometer shelterbelt
along the lower reaches of the mighty Yellow River is expected to
act as a natural defence against seasonal flooding.
</P>
<P>
The central government plans to spend 13 years on the project,
and by 2010 a 30- to 50-meter-wide greenbelt is expected to be
built along the Yellow River.
</P>
<P>
The strong winds and stormy waves often hit dykes violently
during the flood season, according to the commission in charge of
water control on the Yellow River.
</P>
<P>
They say that embankments were a common method of flood
control, but they cost a lot and sometimes inhibit water flow.
</P>
<P>
Green belt can solve some problems of dyke construction and
branches of trees can also be used as flood control materials,
according to experts.
</P>
<P>
The central government will spend 10 million yuan on the
project this year and experimental areas have been set up in 10
counties of Shandong and Henan provinces.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980325.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Expects to Reform Foreign Trade a Great Deal This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 25 (Xinhua) -- China expects to make some
breakthroughs in its foreign trade system reforms this year,
starting with imports and exports.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation will
change the law and administration in accordance with different
import and export commodities and will perfect its export quotas.
</P>
<P>
The quota system for textiles will be changed substantively,
with priority given to more famous brands.
</P>
<P>
China will adjust export quotas on licensed goods and relax
controls on exporters. Export quotas and licensing will be stopped
on 27 kinds of commodities as of April 1.
</P>
<P>
China will give self-control in exports to textiles enterprises
this year and will speed up reforms in imports. It will be
stricter on certificates of origin for export commodities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980325.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Protecting Places of Worship in Tibet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Tibet's places of worship and holy
sites are being protected by the Chinese government, according to
He Feng, an associate research fellow at the Qinghai Social
Science Academy's Tibetology Research Institute.
</P>
<P>
He says that there are more than 3,000 Tibetan temples in the
country that are not only places for religious activities, but
also valuable historic relics. In 1961, the Chinese government put
a group of major Tibetan temples, such as the Potala, Johkang,
Qangdin Lamasery, and Taer Monastery, under state-level protection.
</P>
<P>
Since 1978, the central government has spent 300 million yuan
(36 million US dollars) on repairs in Tibetan temples that were
damaged during the so-called "Cultural Revolution" (1966-1976),
and has allocated one million yuan annually for their maintenance
and has made large-scale repairs to some.
</P>
<P>
He says that the government places considerable importance on
protecting Buddhist statues, paintings and musical instruments
that are enshrined in temples, because many are rare historic
treasures.
</P>
<P>
The government also does not hesitate to crack down on acts of
sabotage or theft of historic relics from temples, and actively
looks for cultural relics that have been lost.
</P>
<P>
Training courses are also held on Tibetan classical works of
literature, history, geography, medicine, and religion at schools
for ethnic minorities.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the China Tibetology Research Center, China has
over 50 institutions engaged in Tibetan studies and more than
2,000 researchers, mainly Tibetan scholars, He says.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980325.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Vice-Premier Meets Guinean Foreign Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier Qian Qichen
said here today that he is convinced that the frequent personnel
contacts between China and Guinea serve the mutual understanding
and improvement of friendly cooperative ties between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
He made his remarks in a meeting with Guinean Foreign Minister
Lamine Kamara.
</P>
<P>
Qian said the two countries have established close relations
since the two forged diplomatic ties nearly four decades ago, and
that the friendship between the two peoples has also deepened.
</P>
<P>
China and Guinea have conducted positive exploration in
cooperation of mutual benefit with the concern of the two leaders
in recent years, Qian said.
</P>
<P>
Qian pointed to the fruitful cooperation in agriculture as well
as minerals which has just started.
</P>
<P>
There exist more diversified content and broader spheres in the
mutual-beneficial cooperation between the two sides, Qian said,
adding that the prospects for such cooperation are optimistic.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government attaches great importance to a proposal
put forward by Guinean President Lansana Conte to further enhance
bilateral cooperation for mutual benefit, Qian said, adding that
it also encourages Chinese enterprises to invest in and jointly
develop Guinea.
</P>
<P>
Qian spoke highly of the Guinean government's efforts in
maintaining peace and stability in western Africa. He said the
stability and prosperity of Guinea itself has positive effects on
the peace and stability of the region.
</P>
<P>
Qian also asked Kamara to convey Chinese President Jiang
Zemin's sincere regards to President Conte.
</P>
<P>
Kamara said the traditional friendly cooperative ties between
his country and China has a solid foundation, and the two sides
have gained results in agricultural cooperation and in other
fields since Conte's China visit in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Guinea enjoys a stable political situation and rich resources,
and is willing to further cooperate with China, Kamara said.
</P>
</TEXT>
