<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Telecom Growth In Northwestern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Northwest China's Shaanxi Province
has shown progress in telecommunications thanks to local
government support.
</P>
<P>
Sources from the provincial posts and telecommunications
administration report that the province had built 10 independent
local telephone networks and installed 1.85 million telephones in
cities by the end of 1997, from 230,000 in 1992.
</P>
<P>
So far, the province has 1.41 million telephone subscribers and
its telephone switching capacity has come up to 2.25 million lines.
</P>
<P>
Telecommunications officials say that five national
long-distance transmission trunk lines using optic cable are
expected to be completed by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
The province has also built mobile telephone networks in all
cities and counties. Mobile phone subscribers had reached 187,000
by the end of 1997. The province also has 2,000 post offices.
</P>
<P>
Sources report that the province is expected to hit 4.1 million
telephone lines by the year 2000 and telephone penetration rate is
expected to reach 10 percent then.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980325.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Columbian Government Willing to Hold Talks with Guerrillas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Columbian government
Tuesday reiterated its "firm willingness to seek a political
solution to the armed conflicts" in the country.
</P>
<P>
A statement released by the presidential office said the
government is ready to discuss with guerrillas their wishes for
changes as long as the guerrilla organization is in real earnest
to push ahead the process of reconciliation among the Columbians.
</P>
<P>
The statement was issued in response to a request by a
guerrilla organization Columbian Revolutionary Armed Forces (FARC)
for talks with representatives not from the central government.
</P>
<P>
The statement made a positive response to the request, saying
the government has approved non-governmental organizations, local
authorities or individuals to hold talks with guerrillas over such
humanitarian issues as the release of 18 government soliders they
captured last December.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the government hoped that the guerrilla
forces will release the soliders as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
FARC Tuesday made public through a radio station in the capital
letters which the 18 government soliders wrote to their families
to show that they were still alive.
</P>
<P>
With the approach of the general elections scheduled on May 31,
the guerrillas have stepped up their activities in various parts
of the country.
</P>
<P>
In exchanges of gunfire with government forces last weekend,
the guerrillas killed 26 people, injured six and captured 26, some
of whom were civilians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
