<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian to Enhance Cooperation in Fighting Crimes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 25 (Xinhua) -- More than 400 interior ministers
and representatives from 30 Asia-Pacific countries agreed here
Wednesday to enhance cooperation in battling the growing
transnational crime in the region.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was contained in the Manila Declaration on the
Prevention and Control of Transnational Crime adopted at the end
of a three-day Asia Regional Ministerial Meeting on Transnational
Crime which ended here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In the declaration, the delegates expressed deep concern about
the increase and expansion of organized criminal activities in the
region, such as trafficking in human beings, transnational
exploitation of women and children, drug trafficking and other
forms of economic crimes.
</P>
<P>
The delegates promised to take concrete measures, including
promoting national and regional actions against transnational
crime, developing effective strategies aimed at defeating the
economic power of criminal organizations and improving the
functioning of law-enforcing institutions.
</P>
<P>
The declaration warned that with rapid economic changes and
advancements in communications and technology, more joint criminal
ventures emerged and many new forms of criminal activities, such
as computer hacking and credit card frauds, have increased.
</P>
<P>
"We recognize the urgent need to make progress in vigorously
promoting international cooperation in criminal matters," the
declaration said.
</P>
<P>
It urged governments to give special attention to extradition,
mutual assistance, witness protection, transfer of prisoners,
seizure and forfeiture of crime proceeds, as well as other forms
of regional and international cooperation in criminal matters.
</P>
<P>
The delegates also appealed to the international community to
give technical assistance to the developing countries in the
region to strengthen their capabilities in combating powerful
transnational crime rings.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, the region's first high-level one on transnational
crime, was sponsored by the Vienna-based United Nations Center for
International Crime Prevention.
</P>
<P>
Russia, France, the United States and three other countries
attended the meeting as observers. The meeting was also attended
by the United Nations Development Program, the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations and other international organizations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
