<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arab Nations Still Concerned About Turko-Israeli </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Despite repeated explanations
from Ankara, Arab countries are apparently still concerned over
the ever-closer military ties between Turkey and Israel.
</P>
<P>
The Daily News quoted Monday an Arab state ambassador to Turkey
as saying that the Turko-Israeli cooperation in military field
might produce a negative impact on the Middle East region.
</P>
<P>
"We have nothing to say against Turkish-Israeli relations. But
when it comes to the discussion of a strategic or military
alliance between these two countries, we, of course, continue to
have concerns," the ambassador said, declining to be named.
</P>
<P>
He said that it is natural that the Arab world is so sensitive
to the every development, especially those in the defense and
military field, between Turkey and the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
"For a comprehensive peace in the Middle East, regional
balances in security and military power should be maintained," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The quickly increasing military cooperation between Turkey and
Israel has prompted grave concern among the Arab countries in this
region, which are afraid that the two would form a military
alliance.
</P>
<P>
The Islamic Summit held in Tehran last December criticized
Ankara without specifying its name for its close military
cooperation with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, a leading Arab country, also voiced its concern over
the Turkish-Israeli closer ties in the military sphere during the
visit of Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail Cem to Cairo last
weekend.
</P>
<P>
Defending its ties with Israel, Turkish government officials
have explained on many occasions that the Turko-Israeli
cooperation is of bilateral nature and not directed against any
third country.
</P>
<P>
Under two defense and military agreements signed early 1996,
Turkey and Israel have rapidly increased their cooperation in
weapon development, joint military training as well as exchange of
visits of military personnel.
</P>
<P>
Last January, the naval forces of Israel, Turkey and the
U.S. held a joint military exercise, code-named "Reliant Mermaid",
in the eastern Mediterranean, triggering strong opposition from
Iran and the Arab nations.
</P>
<P>
Turkey had repeatedly said that that war game was " a routine
search-and-rescue operation", adding that the Arab world need not
feel anxious about it.
</P>
<P>
The Arab countries, most of which have tense relations with
Israel, have said that they have to closely follow the development
of the Turkish-Israeli military cooperation which they warned
might destabilize the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
