<HEADLINE> Roundup: Myanmar, Singapore Further Boost Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, March 25 (Xinhua) -- The 24-hour official visit of
Singapore Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong, which ended here Wednesday
 morning, has further strengthened the ties between the two
countries, especially in the economic field, Myanmar official
media said.
</P>
<P>
The visit, Goh's second to the country since March 1994,
enhanced mutual understanding and friendly ties for mutual
benefit, the media said.
</P>
<P>
"Myanmar has been able to obtain the expertise and know-how
from our Singapore friends in the fields of science and
technology," it said.
</P>
<P>
"Trade has occupied a niche though it is in Singapore's favor
and there exist good prospects for promotion in future," it
pointed out.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, Goh held official talks with Senior-General
Than Shwe, chairman of the Myanmar State Peace and Development
Council and prime minister.
</P>
<P>
A memorandum of understanding on mutual exemption of visas for
holders of diplomatic and official passports was signed during the
stay.
</P>
<P>
The Singapore business mission, which accompanied Prime
Minister Goh, also held discussions with their Myanmar
counterparts which could lead to further expansion of trade and
investment in the years ahead.
</P>
<P>
Economic cooperation between Myanmar and Singapore has
developed rapidly in recent years along with exchange of visits
between state leaders and high-ranking officials.
</P>
<P>
Official figures show that Singapore's total investment in
Myanmar amounted to 1.3 billion U.S. dollars in 65 permitted
projects at the end of 1997, out of 6.6 billion dollars' foreign
investment.
</P>
<P>
According to Singapore statistics, Myanmar and Singapore had a
bilateral trade volume of 800 million dollars in 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
