<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Urged to Sign Landmine-Banning Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 25 (Xinhua) -- The South African Campaign
Against Landmines has called on President Bill Clinton of the
United States to sign a treaty banning landmines.
</P>
<P>
The call coincides with Clinton's 11-day tour of six African
countries, namely Ghana, Uganda, Senegal, South Africa, Botswana
and Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued here Wednesday, the group said it is
ironic the American leader is visiting Africa to discuss economic
recovery support.
</P>
<P>
But it said one of the most critical impending recovery on the
continent is the millions of hectares of land that cannot be
developed as a result of millions of explosive devices.
</P>
<P>
The group said Africa is a continent solidly behind a treaty
prohibiting production, stockpiling, transfer and use of
anti-personnel mines.
</P>
<P>
A total of 38 African countries, including the 14 members of
the Southern African Development Community (SADC), have signed
the treaty.
</P>
<P>
But the U.S. government refuses to approve it.
</P>
<P>
However, the anti-landmine campaign said all the countries
Clinton is touring have played major roles in global efforts to
create a mine-free world.
</P>
<P>
The South African lobby group said while Clinton travels
through Africa, it is collecting signatures protesting against
U.S. policy on the explosive devices.
</P>
<P>
South Africa, a former producer,destroyed more than three
million of its anti-personnel landmine stockpiles before it
signed the international convention last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980325.0250 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Govt Offers Free Treatment for TB Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 25 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government has
mandated all public hospitals across the east African country to
offer free treatment to tuberculosis (TB) patients due to the
alarming increase of the disease.
</P>
<P>
TB cases in Kenya rose quickly from about 10,000 in 1987 to
more than 42,000 in 1997, the Kenya Times newspaper reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
People living in congested environments and those faced with
problems of poor nutrition were at great risk of contracting the
disease, Kenyan Minister for Health Jackson Kalweo warned
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The poor socio-economic status of most of our people coupled
with the rising number of those who are HIV infected and,
therefore, more predisposed to contracting tuberculosis, makes
the TB menace even more worrisome today," he said.
</P>
<P>
He called for intensified public awareness campaigns about the
disease which is now a close rival of the dreaded AIDS as a
killer.
</P>
<P>
The World Health Organization estimates that TB is killing
about three million people in the world annually. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
