<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian President on Foreign, Domestic Policies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Indian President Kocheril Raman
Narayanan said Wednesday that renewed efforts would be made to
improve India's relations with neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
In his address to the joint sitting of both houses of
parliament here, the president reaffirmed India's commitment to
peace and cooperation among all nations and to enhancing its role
in the international arena.
</P>
<P>
He said the Indian government would aim for greater economic
cooperation among developing countries, which is also a priority
of the non-aligned movement.
</P>
<P>
He said that the new government would not compromise on the
country's sovereignty and territorial integrity nor bow to any
pressure on this front.
</P>
<P>
On domestic economic issues, the president said that the
government would step up investment in agriculture and
infrastructure, including foreign investment in core sectors, to
sustain a higher economic growth of 7-8 percent.
</P>
<P>
The government would also strive for poverty eradication
through generating employment and sustaining a higher GDP (gross
domestic product) growth, he said.
</P>
<P>
While stressing that "India can and shall be built by Indians,"
the president said that foreign direct investment (FDI) will be
encouraged in the core sectors of the economy and in physical
infrastructure development.
</P>
<P>
Nayayanan said that the country's agriculture had suffered due
to declining investment in the past. The new government would
earmark up to 60 percent of the planned fund for this crucial
segment.
</P>
<P>
"Urgent measures will be taken to substantially step up
investment in infrastructure sectors, including power, roads and
bridges, railways, inland waterways, sea ports, shipping,
airports, telecommunications and information technology," he said.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
