<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mugabe Denies Buying Castle in Scottish Highlands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert
Mugabe Tuesday night dismissed as a smear campaign reports that
he is buying a castle in the Scottish highlands, the Herald daily
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
This is the second time he has rebutted such reports in as
many months. The first time was during his birthday last month.
</P>
<P>
Reports in the Sunday Times of Britain at the weekend said
that the president was trying to buy a castle in Scotland and
that he was already being dubbed the "king" of Scotland.
</P>
<P>
But a statement from his office last night said that the
report alleging that the president was trying to buy a castle
should be dismissed with the contempt it deserves.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the article was part of a wider smear
campaign launched by the president's detractors, most of whom
stand opposed to the land reform program adopted by the
government, to reverse the colonial legacy in this country.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the president had already publicly invited
the British government to take over and sell all properties he is
alleged to personally own in the United Kingdom, and use the
proceeds for charitable purposes.
</P>
<P>
The Sunday Times alleged that Mugabe had fallen in love with
the Scottish highlands during numerous visits in the past 17
years. It said that the president was believed to have made
inquiries about buying an ancient Scottish seat during the last
Commonwealth summit, held in Edinburgh in October last year.
</P>
<P>
It then listed a number of stately properties the newspaper
said were suitable for sale.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
