<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Potential For Developing New Markets (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Because of the "soft landing" for
China's economy, consumer demand in urban areas is expected to
provide new possibilities in China's consumer market, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
Until the mid-1980s, China's consumer goods were mainly
foodstuff and items for daily use, but the content and scale of
today's market are remarkably changed.
</P>
<P>
New housing demand in the next two years is estimated at 1.2
billion square meters, to take just one example, and annual real
estate sales are expected to be 60 billion yuan (about 7.2 billion
US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Demand for electronics and information is expected to grow 30
percent every year, with annual sales reaching 5.4 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Some 300,000 old private motor vehicles are expected to be
replaced every year, and demand this year will exceed 1.65 million
cars.
</P>
<P>
Over 70 million urban residents in China need certain community
services. Last year, the prices of 20 services rose 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
Tourism is another sector with rapid growth. China's revenues
from international tourists exceeded 10 billion US dollars for two
consecutive years, while domestic tourism had over 20 percent
annual growth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980325.0256 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Potentials for Developing New Markets (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Consulting and advertising have grown 20 and 40 percent
respectively, and are expected to do a total of 130 billion
yuan in business by 2000.
</P>
<P>
Residential indoor fitting-up business is growing at an annual
rate of over 30 percent, and is worth about 60 billion yuan and
expected to rise to 100 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Recent years have also seen good growth and huge profits in the
medical, entertainment, and catering sectors.
</P>
<P>
The constant improvement in the standard of living and in
consumer standards indicates that China has entered a new period,
one analyst observed, and people's lives have gone from
quantity-oriented to quality-oriented.
</P>
<P>
However, because of regional disparities in consumption and
the backwardness of certain markets, more time is needed for
China's new markets to improve themselves.
</P>
<P>
Some people are saying that new efforts are needed for the
consumer environment, and that shopping by credit needs to be
encouraged in the housing, automobile, and medical care
markets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
