<HEADLINE> EU, Kenya Join Hands in Marketing Kenya's Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 25 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government and the
European Union (EU) will spend 360 million Shillings (60 million
U.S. Dollars) to market Kenya abroad as a tourist destination,
local press reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Tourism and Wildlife Minister Henry Kosgey was quoted as
saying that the purse will be managed under a joint endowment
fund partly for the protection of fauna and wildlife and partly
for aggressive tourism marketing campaign home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
However, the east African country would go a long way in
restoring its status as a leading tourist destination on African
continent, he said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan government has started emergency work on
infrastructural repairs following recent El Nino rains, which
will be completed in the next three months, he said following a
meeting with EU head of delegation Lutz Salzmann.
</P>
<P>
Salzmann said it was "extremely important" for the Kenyan
government to encourage the private sector to "play a larger
role" in tourism, the traditional largest foreign money earner
for the country.
</P>
<P>
The EU is the most important source of tourists for the Kenyan
market since it contributes about half of all tourists coming to
Kenya, said Kosgey.  
</P>
