<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Newly-Discovered City Wall Gives Outlines Of Old Chinese Kingdom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, March 25 (Xinhua) -- The recent discovery of a
600-meter city wall in south China has given archaeologists an
outline of the Shu Kingdom 3,500 years ago in modern-day Sichuan
Province.
</P>
<P>
A north-south city wall was found on the northern part of the
Sanxingdui Ruins in Guanghan City, 40 kilometers north of Chengdu,
the capital of Sichuan.
</P>
<P>
Since the 1920s, Chinese and foreign archaeologists have done
many studies of the Ba-Shu culture in the province. In 1986, the
discovery of two large sacrificial pits there got a great deal of
attention.
</P>
<P>
"The newly-excavated wall, 2.8 meter high and 20 meter wide, is
made of rammed earth, on which a great number of pottery pieces
have been found," said experts. They determined that the age of
the wall could date back to 3,500 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Seven pits used for sacrificial offerings were also unearthed on
the southern part of the Ruins. Most of them were three meters
long and 1.5 meter wide, in which body remains, jade, elephant
tusks and stone-made balls have been collected.
</P>
<P>
Experts believed the new discovery will shed light on the study
of religious ceremonies and sacrificial activities held in the
region in ancient times.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
