<HEADLINE> International Medical Team Performs Surgery On Chinese Children </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Wang Li, an 11-year-old girl from
a small village in east China's Jiangsu Province who never smiled
or laughed because of her cleft palate, was able to smile for the
first time after plastic surgery done by specialists from
Operation Smile International (OSI).
</P>
<P>
Wang was one of the lucky 2,000 Chinese children who got help
from OSI, an international medical organization made up of
volunteers from different countries.
</P>
<P>
"I can go to school now, and I want to be a useful person in
the future," the girl said excitedly. Her father also said that
the successful surgery had helped "restore confidence for my
daughter's future."
</P>
<P>
The operation was done at Gulou Hospital in Nanjing, Jiangsu's
capital, and was broadcast live to more than 1,000 people who
celebrated OSI's 15th anniversary at the World Trade Center in New
York.
</P>
<P>
Han Kai, a member of the medical team, said that OSI, which was
founded in the United States in 1982, will provide free surgery
every year for children in various countries, and that more than
15,000 children in 15 countries have got operations because of
OSI. 
</P>
</TEXT>
