<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> People in Gansu No Longer Have To Face Grain Shortages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, March 25 (Xinhua) -- In northwest China's Gansu
Province, people see the self-sufficiency in grain supplies as the
biggest change since China started its reforms and opening up
twenty years ago.
</P>
<P>
Because of harsh conditions and frequent droughts, Gansu was
always short of grain, but this changed with the reforms. The
province has had from 6 to 7 billion kg of grain for two
continuous years.
</P>
<P>
Although Gansu suffered from droughts in 1997, it still
harvested 7.65 billion kilograms of grain, the second highest
output in its history. And it now has more than four billion
kilograms of grain in storage, a record high.
</P>
<P>
This means more than 300 kilograms per person and self
sufficiency in grain.
</P>
<P>
Gansu has also changed the situation with other products, with
production of 740,000 tons of meat, 150,000 tons of eggs, and
115,000 tons of milk in 1997.
</P>
<P>
It has also become an important supply center for vegetables,
fruits, and potatoes.
</P>
<P>
Before the reforms, 72 percent of its rural people lived in
poverty, and Gansu was infamous for this. Now, after fourteen
years of poverty-relief work, 10 million of these people
eliminated poverty. A fifth of the peasants in the province now
lead better lives. In 1997, peasants made 1,210 yuan annually per
person, up 110 yuan from the previous year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
