<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2 Airborn Warning Planes Arrive in Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Two airborne warning and control
system (AWACS) planes which Japan bought from the United States
arrived at an Air Self-Defense Force (ASDF) base in central Japan
on Wednesday, a report reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
The two E-767 AWACS planes are part of the four U.S. military
surveillance planes which Japan had ordered from the United States.
</P>
<P>
The two remodeled Boeing 767 passenger planes flew into the
base in Hamamatsu, Shizuoka Prefecture, shortly before noon, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
They are Japan's first-ever AWACS planes, which are known as
"flying headquarters" because of their ability to track the
positions of all aircraft, naval vessels and ground troops within
a radius of 800 kilometers and send the information to command
authorities.
</P>
<P>
The AWACS has a disk-shaped, jam-resistant radar on top of its
body and can fly for 12 hours without refueling.
</P>
<P>
AWACS planes cost between 54 billion and 57 billion yen (about
415 million and 439 million U.S. dollars) each.
</P>
<P>
Compared with the E-2C "Hawkeye," the E-767s can cover a wider
range of areas and are particularly good at monitoring at low
altitudes, Defense Agency officials said.
</P>
<P>
The Defense Agency plans to deploy two more AWACS planes at the
end of fiscal 1998, which ends March 31, 1999, according to the
report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
