<DOCNO> XIE19980325.0281 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Deposit Rates Soar in Indonesia After Hike in SBIs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Commercial banks in Indonesia
have raised interest rates on one-month deposits to as high as
67.5 percent, following the sharp rise in central bank certificate
note (SBI) rate on Monday, local leading newspapers reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The rates are the highest seen during the past three decades,
said the reports.
</P>
<P>
Analysts warned that excessively high interest rates, if
maintained for a long period of time, will annihilate an already
weak banking sector.
</P>
<P>
"If banks have to offer high rates they will eventually
collapse because they cannot afford to pay the gains which will
accrue to deposits," banking expert Sultan Remy Sjahdeni said.
</P>
<P>
State Bank Dagang Negara (BDN) offered the highest interest
rates to its customers Tuesday. The bank's rates for a one-month
deposit more than doubled, jumping to 67.5 percent per annum, up
from 33 percent the day before.
</P>
<P>
Interest rates on state Bank Rakyat Indonesia one month
deposits rose from 33 percent to 50 percent per annum, while State
Bank Negara Indonesia (BNI) raised interest rates from 33 percent
to 56 percent for one-month deposits.
</P>
<P>
The country's largest private bank, Bank Central Asia (BCA),
hiked one month interest rates to 54.5 percent from 32 percent.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Bank Indonesia, the central bank, raised its
certificate interest rate (SBIs) sharply. Rates on overnight SBIs
stayed at 40 percent, rates on two-day were raised to 41 percent,
three-to-six day rates were raised to 42 percent, one week rates
were raised to 43 percent, two-week rates to 44 percent and one
month rates to 45 percent.
</P>
<P>
When announcing the SBI rate increase on Monday, Bank Indonesia
Governor Sjahril Sabirin said the move was intended to absorb
excess liquidity in the market which could lead to higher
inflation and further weakening of the rupiah.
</P>
<P>
SBI is short-term rupiah-denominated obligations issued by the
central bank to drain excess liquidity from the market.
</P>
<P>
A banking expert questioned the efficacy of using interest
rates to shore up the rupiah for a long period.
</P>
<P>
"It will be effective in the very short-term only," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, the World Bank's country director Dennis De Tray said
here Tuesday, "if the interest rate is not raised now, the
inflation rate can go up very quickly and the rupiah can drop very
substantially ... Nobody likes a high interest rate, but right now
it is essential to stabilize the economy."
</P>
<P>
The rupiah has lost more than 70 percent of its value against
the U.S. dollar since July last year and the prices of basic
commodities in the country also increased by 50 to 400 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980325.0282 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study Claims 10 Million Americans Still Experience Hunger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Despite strong economic
growth, 10 million people in the United States, including 4
million children, do not get enough to eat.
</P>
<P>
According to a study released Tuesday by Cornell University and
the National Center for Health Statistics, six percent of American
children and 14 percent of the poor go hungry.
</P>
<P>
The study's lead author, Cornell doctoral candidate Katherine
Alaimo, said that it is not just the unemployed or single-parent
families who do not get enough to eat.
</P>
<P>
"More Americans who do not have enough to eat live in families
of married couples with children than in other types of families,"
Alaimo said.
</P>
<P>
The study found that 4.5 million non-Hispanic whites, 2.4
million non-Hispanic blacks and 2.4 million Mexican Americans are
underfed.
</P>
<P>
Alaimo said the issue is still a serious problem in the United
States, and it is not limited to low-income persons, specific
racial or ethnic groups, certain family types or the unemployed.
</P>
<P>
She also claims families that go hungry are also twice as
likely as others to forego medical insurance.
</P>
<P>
"Many low-income, uninsured Americans may be making the choice
between health care and paying for food," She said.
</P>
<P>
The study of 30,000 people was conducted from 1988 to 1994. It
will be published in the March issue of the American Journal of
Public Health. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
