<HEADLINE> Mexico Acts to Cushion Shock of Oil Price Slump </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, March 24 (Xinhua) -- The Mexican government has
cut public spending and slowed down its economic pace in an effort
to cushion the negative impact of the global decline in oil prices.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of this year, the Mexican government has
cut its public spending by 1.5 percent (200 million U.S. dollars),
and adjusted the economic growth rate to 4.8 percent from the
planned 5.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
It has stablized the currency market, reducing two million
pesos (235,000 dollars) worth of currency in circulation.
</P>
<P>
Other measures include encouraging exports of manufactured,
agricultural and animal husbandry products and reducing the volume
of oil exports together with other oil-producing countries.
</P>
<P>
The local media reported that more measures such as further
spending cuts and tax raises were under discussion.
</P>
<P>
Income from oil exports accounts for 30 percent of Mexico's
foreign currency.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the global oil price crisis, Mexico's foreign
currency income in February declined by 248 million dollars from
January to 562 million dollars, down 37.4 percent from the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
This caused the country's trade deficit to rise by 49 million
dollars from January to 635 million dollars in February. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
