<HEADLINE> 105 Indians Killed in Tornado </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 25 (Xinhua) -- At least 105 people were
killed, 1,100 injured and thousands rendered homeless when a
severe tornado swept through several villages in two adjoining
districts of India's West Bengal and Orissa states Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The tornado with a wind speed of 160-180 kilometers per hour
killed 50 people in Sijua Satta village in West Bengal's Midnapore
district. It also killed 16 in Gobarghata, Dairat and Madhapur
villages in adjoining Balasore district of Orissa State, the
Hindustan Times said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
West Bengal's Relief Minister S. R. Mahato said most of the
deaths were due to house collapses. He added that more than 8,000
people were rendered homeless and nearly 800 dwellings destroyed.
</P>
<P>
State Chief Secretary Manish Gupta said that the
telecommunications network was totally disrupted by the tornado
and that rescuers and medical teams have already reached the
affected villages.
</P>
<P>
In Orissa State, Revenue Minister Jagannath Patnaik said the
storm snapped telecommunications links and uprooted electric
poles.
</P>
<P>
President K. R. Narayanan and Prime Minister A. B. Vajpayee
have expressed distress over the deaths and devastation caused by
the tornado. 
</P>
</TEXT>
