<HEADLINE> Justice Department Asked to Study Race and Traffic Stops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 24 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. House of
Representatives passed a bill Tuesday requiring the Justice
Department to determine the racial breakdown for routine traffic
stops made by state and local police.
</P>
<P>
"There are very few of us in this country who have not been
stopped at one time for an alleged traffic violation that we
thought constituted really simple racial harassment," said
Representative John Conyers, a Democrat, who is black.
</P>
<P>
Conyers, the ranking Democrat on the Judiciary Committee and the
chief author of the bill, cited figures showing that blacks, who
make up about 14 percent of the population, account for 72 percent
of drivers pulled over for routine traffic stops.
</P>
<P>
The bill, which passed by voice vote, would require the
attorney general to conduct a study on traffic stops and include
the age and race or ethnic background of the person stopped, the
alleged traffic violation and whether car searches were conducted
and contraband discovered.
</P>
<P>
Republicans on the Judiciary Committee of the House of
Representatives pushed through an amendment making clear that the
data acquired under the study cannot be used in discrimination
cases.
</P>
<P>
Representative Henry Hyde, a Republican and the Judiciary
Committee chairman, said the legislation has the support of the
administration and can help promote police awareness of the
problems of "profiling," in which cars are stopped based on the
race, age or dress of the occupants.
</P>
<P>
He said there were a "growing number of reported incidents and
allegations that black American males are being stopped for no
reason" and in violation of Fourth Amendment prohibitions against
unlawful searches and seizures. The Senate has not passed the
bill. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980325.0290 </DOCNO>
