<HEADLINE> Czech Tourism Slides in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Tourism income of the Czech
Republic was 3.65 billion U.S. dollars in 1997, a 10.5 percent
drop from the previous year.
</P>
<P>
In remarks published by the local press Tuesday, The Czech
Regional Development and Housing Ministry said the proportion of
tourism income in the gross domestic product (GDP) decreased last
year to seven percent from 7.3 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Foreign exchange income from tourism fell from 18.8 percent to
16.2 percent in the overall foreign trade figure, the ministry
said.
</P>
<P>
The Czech Republic is rich in tourism resources, with Prague
enjoying the fame as a model of architectural art.
</P>
<P>
Overall, tourism income has been rising steadily since 1992
with the number of foreign travelers increasing annually.
</P>
<P>
It is believed the unusual floods last July in eastern areas of
the Czehc Republic are the main reason leading to last year's
reduction in tourism.
</P>
<P>
Political instability, deteriorating social order and poor
services are also believed to contribute to the 1997 slide.
</P>
</TEXT>
