<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Manila Acts to Stabilize Financial Situation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 25 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine peso has recently
shown signs of stabilization due to improvement in the regional
financial situation and the Philippine Central Bank's efforts in
combating the currency crisis.
</P>
<P>
During the past 10 trading days, the peso appreciated from 40
pesos per U.S. dollar to 37.31 pesos a dollar, the highest in
recent months. Compared with the lowest level in January this
year, the peso rallied 18 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the composite index of the Philippine Stock Exchange
also went up gradually, reaching 2,310 points on Monday, the
highest level since the financial storm began hitting Southeast
Asia in July last year.
</P>
<P>
The extremely high interest rates which were killing the
country's economy also began falling down. The bankers have agreed
to bring down their prime lending rates to between 17 and 23
percent this week.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts attributed these to the improvement of the
regional financial situation. However, Central Bank Governor
Gabriel Singson said more credit should be given to the various
reforms and measures taken by the country to stabilize the peso.
</P>
<P>
After the currency crisis started last July, the central bank
first strengthened its management of liquidity in the financial
system.
</P>
<P>
It raised its overnight borrowing and lending rates to 32
percent and 34 percent respectively, almost double the pre-peso
depreciation level. In the meantime, it increased banks' liquidity
reserve to 8 percent from 2 percent on top of the 13 percent
statutory reserve.
</P>
<P>
But the tightened liquidity failed to strengthen the peso since
it was mainly affected by the turbulence in the Thai baht and the
Indonesian rupiah. Therefore the central bank lowered the
borrowing and lending rates subsequently.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, the bank strengthened its supervision of the banks'
foreign exchange trading.
</P>
<P>
To stop the banks from speculating in the peso, the central
bank reduced their allowable overbought foreign exchange position
from 20 percent to 5 percent while raising their oversold position
to 20 percent from 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
It also required the banks to consolidate the accounts with
their subsidiaries and affiliates to prevent possible
circumvention of the monetary authorities by coursing foreign
exchange transactions through the subsidiaries and affiliates.
</P>
<P>
The central bank also introduced a currency risk protection
program called the "non-deliverable forward" facility. The
facility eased the strain on the spot market and satisfied those
who wanted to buy dollar to cover immature foreign currency
obligations in fears of a further peso depreciation.
</P>
<P>
Finally, the central bank reinforced the financial system.
Since the crisis was triggered by excessive bad loans brought
about by the real estate sector, the central bank capped the
banks' exposure to the sector to no more than 20 percent of their
loan portfolio.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the rapid growth of bad loans, it ordered the banks
to set up 2 percent of their loan portfolio as a loan-loss
provision within three years. Later the bank decided to accelerate
the implementation of this rule.
</P>
<P>
To help lower the interest rates, the central bank also
re-opened a 30-day lending window to the banks, set up a
peso-dollar swap scheme for banks without government securities
holdings and began purchasing the government securities at market
rates.
</P>
<P>
As a result of these efforts, the Philippine financial system
has begun stabilizing, but it does not mean that the financial
storm has been over. The peso might depreciate again if the
currencies in other countries fall anew into turmoil. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
