<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Costa Rica Demands Greater Efforts in Drug War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Costa Rica's President Jose
Maria Figueres Tuesday urged countries in the western hemisphere
to exert more efforts to fight drug dealing and money
laundering.
</P>
<P>
"All countries have the same responsibility to eliminate the
problem of drug supply and demand," Figueres said on the first day
of the 16th International Conference on Drug Fighting.
</P>
<P>
These two factors are "part of the problem and are also a road
to the solution," Figueres said.
</P>
<P>
The conference, sponsored by the U.S. Anti-drug
Agency (DEA) and the Costa Rican Ministry of Public Security, is
aimed at promoting regional cooperation in fighting drugs in the
western hemisphere.
</P>
<P>
Anti-drug police officers from more than 30 countries attended
the meeting, which is scheduled to end Thursday. Among those
attending are General Jose Serrano, head of the Colombian National
Police and Thomas Constantine, head of the DEA.
</P>
<P>
During the conference, the results of work performed by South
and Central American countries and Mexico will be evaluated by
representatives from Germany, Spain, France, Italy and Japan.
</P>
<P>
Some of the countries with the largest narcotic production are
located in South America, while the U.S. is considered the major
consumer of drugs worldwide.
</P>
<P>
According to information released by the U.S. State Department,
Peru, Colombia and Bolivia produce almost 98 percent of the
cocaine consumed worldwide. Every year, these countries illegally
export about 760 tons of cocaine, while the U.S. is the recipient
of more than 300 tons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
