<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia to Opt for Mexican Model in Debt Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia is to adopt a revised
version of the Mexican model to solve its private sector overseas
debt crisis, a senior official said.
</P>
<P>
This would likely include a grace period of a few years and
provide an affordable exchange rate for the rupiah, the national
currency, against the U.S. dollar, State Minister of the
Empowerment of State Enterprises Tanri Abeng said here Tuesday
night following a meeting between the country's debt settlement
team and experts from Japan.
</P>
<P>
However, he did not give further details as the model is still
being refined, including through further discussions with the
International Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
The rupiah has been under severe pressure since July last year,
plunging to its lowest level of 17,000 to the U.S. dollar in
January, compared with 2,450 rupiah in the pre-crisis period in
July. It is currently trading at about 8,500 per dollar.
</P>
<P>
This has made most indebted companies technically bankrupt as
their foreign debts exceed their equity. Mexico experienced a
similar problem in 1984, Tanri said.
</P>
<P>
At the end of December last year, Indonesia's foreign debt
totaled 137.424 billion U.S. dollars, including 63.462 billion
dollars in government debt and 73.926 billion dollars in private
sector debt.
</P>
<P>
The minister explained that the aim of the model is not just to
lessen demand for dollars and thus shore up the ailing rupiah but
also to help the private sector resume business to reduce
unemployment.
</P>
<P>
"I think the Mexican model is workable," he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister also said Japan has accepted Indonesia's proposal
to settle its private sector foreign debts with Japanese banks
over a period of three to four years.
</P>
<P>
"But the terms of repayment will be adjusted according to
(changing) conditions in Indonesia and must first be discussed
with the IMF," he said.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that 40 percent of Indonesia's private sector
debts are owed to Japanese banks and companies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
