<HEADLINE> Bush Fires Halt Flights in Northern Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Smoke and haze from forest fires
in northern Thailand forced the Thai Airways to cancel on Tuesday
all its domestic flights from Chiang Mai to Mae Hong Son Province.
</P>
<P>
Thai Airways officials at Chiang Mai international airport said
visibility there was only 800 meters, far below the required 2,500
meters, the Bangkok Post reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, hundreds of volunteers have been fighting a losing
battle to put out bush fires which have been raging on Doi
Inthanon Mountain, the country's highest, for the last three days.
</P>
<P>
The Doi Inthanon forest fire control unit said more than 1,600
hectares of forests have been destroyed over the past three days.
</P>
<P>
Chiang Mai-based Northern Meteorological Center said several
provinces in the north were affected by thick smoke.
</P>
<P>
The center warned that the situation could worsen during the
upcoming hot season when temperatures could exceed 40 degrees
Celsius.
</P>
<P>
Bush fires have affected several parts of Thailand, especially
the north, in the past few weeks due to the dry weather and the
slash-and-burn farming by forest encroachers.
</P>
<P>
Reports from Huay Kha Khaeng wildlife sanctuary said thick
smoke had blanketed Mae Sot district in the northern Tak Province,
stinging the eyes of local residents and causing respiratory
problems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
