<HEADLINE> Dhaka to Frame New Law to Protect Women, Children </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi Prime Minister Sheikh
Hasina told the parliament Tuesday that her government had decided
to enact a more effective and complete law to contain crimes
against women and children, press reports here said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
An experts' committee is now examining framing of a new law to
cope with the changing nature and volume of such crimes, and
secure public life, the prime minister was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Experience had proved that the existing laws were inadequate to
deal with such crimes, she noted.
</P>
<P>
Cases relating to terrorist acts like acid-throwing, rape,
child-trafficking and killing for dowry needed quick disposal, she
stressed.
</P>
<P>
"Addressing the offenses against women and children is very
important and is a must," because women and children constitute
more than two-thirds (70.63 percent) of the country's 124.3
million population, she said.
</P>
<P>
She said that the proposed law "should also have provisions for
penalizing the criminal for the loss or injury caused to the
victim."
</P>
<P>
"Mere enactment of legislation or a government initiative is
not enough," she said, adding "all social forces irrespective of
their political beliefs and affiliations should come forward to
uproot the social curse."
</P>
<P>
Besides, law enforcers should perform their duty neutrally and
all concerned should make concerted efforts for this, the prime
minister added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
