<DOCNO> XIE19980325.0306 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Farmer Helps Poor out of Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Farmer Lei Renyi in northwest
China's Shaanxi Province has helped more than 10,000 of his
country people out of poverty in the past six years, and was
chosen as one of the country's top 10 poverty-relief masters.
</P>
<P>
Wulipu, Lei's home village in Weinan city, had long been
plagued by poverty. In the mid-1980s, Lei, together with other
villagers, began to start township enterprises. And now, the
village has grown into a group, involving agriculture, industry,
and business, with more than 200 million yuan in annual output
value, and nearly 3,000 yuan in per-capita income.
</P>
<P>
A better-off Lei turned to Yanyu Village at the northern foot
of the Qinling Mountains in 1991. He invited some experts on
agriculture and forestry to work out an outline to help the
village develop apples and cash forests.
</P>
<P>
He sponsored some villagers to visit developed areas elsewhere,
to go to college, to set up schools, and to open training classes
on science and technology. He also set aside 40,000 yuan for the
village to start business.
</P>
<P>
As a result, each farmer in the long starved Yanyu can have 500
kilograms of grain, and 1,500 yuan in annual income.
</P>
<P>
Another three villages and a township have also benefited from
Lei's effort. Now, the city has 315 poverty-relief pairs of the
kind, involving approximately 100,000 people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
