<DOCNO> XIE19980325.0310 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Korda Bounces Out, Hingis Overtakes Serena Williams </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Australian Open champion Petr
Korda of Czech Republic saw another world number one hope all but
evaporated when he bounced out of the Lipton tennis Championships
before reaching quarter-final on Tuesday in Key Biscayne, Florida.
</P>
<P>
While world number one Martina Hingis of Switzerland fought
back solid challenge from Serena Williams in an tense
quarter-final encounter.
</P>
<P>
Korda, who surrendered twice to take over the world top ranking
from American Pete Sampras earlier this year, fell to 20th-ranked
Tim Henman of Britain in the fourth round.
</P>
<P>
The 30-year-old Czech could have become number one by reaching
the semi-finals this week.
</P>
<P>
Hingis just survived the younger of the beaded Williams sisters
in a 6-3, 1-6, 7-6 (7-4) victory.
</P>
<P>
The Swiss sensation, 17, who edged her one-year-old-younger
opponent on experience, saved two match points and needed a
third-set tie-break to move up to next round.
</P>
<P>
Fifth-ranked Greg Rusedski of Britain also missed his chance to
usurp Sampras' throne as he was upended 6-2, 6-2 by Thomas Enqvise
of Sweden.
</P>
<P>
The only player left with a chance to pull down Sampras from
his throne this week is third-ranked Marcelo Rios of Chile, who
can claim the top spot by winning the tournament.
</P>
<P>
The third-seeded Rios moved a step up by a 6-2, 6-3 victory
over Goran Ivanisevic of Croatia.
</P>
<P>
American Jeff Tarango upset sixth-seeded Russian Yevgeny
Kafelnikov to advance to the quarter-fianls, 3-6, 6-3, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
Sixteen-year-old Russian prodigy Anna Kournikova needed just 50
minutes to crush out ninth-seeded Sapniard Conchita Martinez, 6-3,
6-0 in a fourth-round match. 
</P>
