<HEADLINE> Russian Ripples Benign, Say EU Associates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, March 24 (Xinhua) -- The shakeup in Russia's
government will not have any negative impact on its domestic
situation or the international community, parliamentary leaders of
associate members of the European Union (EU) said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The leaders made this observation at a news conference here
after ending a two-day meeting. European Parliament President
Gil-Robles Gil-Delgado, and parliamentary leaders from ten EU
associate member countries, attended the conference, the fifth of
its sort.
</P>
<P>
The big reshuffle of the Russian government would not affect
Russia's stability or its foreign policy orientation, said Jan
Diaconescu, chairman of Romania's Chamber of Deputies.
</P>
<P>
Gil-Delgado agreed but stressed that it was necessary to find
the real reason behind the reshuffle, and watch the main
guidelines set by Russia in the future.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin appointed Energy Minister Sergei Kiriyenko as acting
prime minister after he sacked Viktor Chernomyrdin and the entire
cabinet on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The reshuffle came after Yeltsin censured the government during
weekend meetings for its chronic failure to pay back wages and
pensions to millions of Russians.
</P>
<P>
Russian President Boris Yeltsin's shakeup would not hamper the
process of European integration, said the Latvian Parliament
Chairman Alfreds Chepanis and Vice-Chairman of Hungarian National
Assembly Karodi Maria.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin's decision, said Chairman of Lithuanian Parliament
Vytautas Landsbergis, aimed at deepening Russia's reform.
</P>
<P>
Other parliamentary leaders at the meeting came from Bulgaria,
Poland, the Czech Republic, the Slovak Republic, Slovenia and
Estonia. 
</P>
