<HEADLINE> Thailand Urges Myanmar to Prevent Border Incursion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Thailand has urged Myanmar to
prevent incursion by Myanmar-based Karen guerrillas into Thailand
in order to demonstrate unity of the Association of Southeast
Asian Nations (ASEAN).
</P>
<P>
Myanmar Ambassador to Thailand Hla Maung was summoned to the
Thai Foreign Ministry on Tuesday to hear a letter of protest
against an armed attack by Karen guerrillas on a refugee camp on
the Thai-Myanmar border, Wednesday's Bangkok Post reported.
</P>
<P>
The protest letter clearly identified the Democratic Karen
Buddhist Army (DKBA), a Karen splinter group, as the attacker.
</P>
<P>
"The incident affected the Yangon-Bangkok relationship, both of
which are members of ASEAN," Thai Deputy Foreign Minister
Sukhumbhand Paribatra said after his meeting with the Myanmar
envoy.
</P>
<P>
He added that both countries should show the international
community that ASEAN members are ready to cooperate with one
another, and that the two countries could walk hand in hand to a
meeting of ASEAN foreign ministers.
</P>
<P>
The annual meeting of ASEAN foreign ministers takes place in
July. Myanmar joined the grouping last year.
</P>
<P>
Some DKBA guerrillas crossed into Thailand on Monday and raided
the refugee camp, killing one person and wounding 13 others. In
the past, DKBA forces carried out scores of attacks on Karen
refugees taking shelter in Thailand, believing that the displaced
population harbors and supports the DKBA's rivals.
</P>
<P>
A top Myanmar general said at the weekend that Myanmar troops
were not involved in the recent spate of attacks and had no
control over the Karen guerrillas. He said the Thai Army could
take any action deemed necessary to counter the raids, according
to the Bangkok Post.  
</P>
</TEXT>
