<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Traffic Police Trying To Serve People </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Getting a flat tire on your
bicycle out on the highway all of a sudden can be a real headache,
but not necessarily if you happen to be in Nanning, capital of
south China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Any traffic police station there can provide you with
medicines, a bicycle pump, a map, a weather report, and the
policemen may even roll up their sleeves and give you a hand.
</P>
<P>
This under-developed city has 1.28 million people from
different ethnic groups and 220,000 motor vehicles and no money to
improve its infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
However, the city is known for its orderly traffic and lack of
accidents, thanks to the efforts of the traffic administration.
</P>
<P>
"Traffic police should set a good example for the common
people, as a great way to contribute to the city's promotion of
ethic progress," said one traffic administration officer.
</P>
<P>
In the last two years, the city's traffic police have dealt
with 12,370 unlawful activities and in the second half of last
year, helped repair over 2,000 motor vehicles and bicycles free of
charge and helped get 840 seriously-ill people to hospital.
</P>
<P>
To improve people's traffic awareness, the traffic
administration organizes publicity campaigns regularly, and since
last August, has taken steps to keep drivers from sounding their
horns in downtown areas. A test by the department on September 1,
1997 showed that the noise level in the downtown area was 69.9
decibels, which is below the state's level.
</P>
<P>
In the past two years, the city's Vehicle Administration has
bought 25 computers to help its staff provide more convenient and
accurate services for vehicle owners.
</P>
<P>
Only a year ago, an applicant had to wait 15 days before
getting a driver's license, but now the whole procedure takes only
one hour.
</P>
<P>
Its complaint box and phone have 30 volunteers to help its
staff, a move that has been praised by the general public.
</P>
<P>
One senior officer in charge of traffic explains: "Traffic
police should provide a range of services for the public and play
a leading role in shaping a new image for the city." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
