<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WB, ADB Pledge "Safety net" aid to Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 25 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank (WB) and the Asian
Development Bank (ADB) have pledged to provide humanitarian aid to
Indonesia under a short-term safety-net program in order to help
the country overcome its economic turmoil, Antara News Agency
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The expression was made Tuesday here by executives of the two
banks when meeting with Indonesian Vice President B.J. Habibie.
</P>
<P>
World Bank's country director Dennis De Tray said after the
meeting besides the humanitarian aid, his institution would also
encouraged other donors to extend help to the poor here.
</P>
<P>
"We have a very careful assessment of food needs, contraception
needs and hospital supports ...," De Tray said.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian government needs at least 1.5 billion U.S.
dollars worth of essential commodities for this year, comprising 1
billion U.S. dollars for the importation of rice, and the
remainder for other staples, medicine and hospital equipment,
official sources said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, ADB's program director Shoji Nishimoto said the bank
would allocate up to 300 million U.S. dollars for social
safety-net activities in Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
"Our assistance will primarily focus on restructuring and
modernizing the banking sector, but beyond that we are also
working on social safety net, basic education and health
services," Nishimoto said.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank has committed 4.5 billion U.S. dollars and the
ADB 3.5 billion U.S. dollars to the 43-billion-U.S. dollar rescue
package organized by the International Monetary Fund (IMF) for the
country last year.
</P>
<P>
De Tray disclosed the World Bank plans to have a technical
meeting in Washington on April 1 to discuss with donot partners on
how to address humanitarian issues.  
</P>
</TEXT>
