<HEADLINE> Czech Reactions to Russia's Government Change </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, March 24 (Xinhua) -- The government reshuffle in Moscow
would not lead to a change in Russia's foreign policy, Rodolf
Hykl, the news bureau chief from the Czech Foreign Ministry said
here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Czech government has no reason to believe that the change
in Russia's government personnel will bring about a change in its
foreign policy, or a change in its position on NATO expansion,
Hykl was quoted as saying by the Czech News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The Czech government believes Russian President Boris Yeltsin's
dismissal of the cabinet headed by Viktor Chernomyrdin aimed to
"further strengthen Russia's reform policy," Deputy Prime Minister
and Agriculture Minister Josef Lux was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
President Yeltsin dismissed the entire cabinet headed by Prime
Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin Monday.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday Yeltsin spoke highly of the work of dismissed
Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov and Defense Minister
Igor Sergeyev at a meeting with presidential administration
executives.
</P>
<P>
This suggests that the two men are likely to retain their posts
in a new government yet to be formed, Kremlin spokesman Sergei
Yastrzhembsky was quoted as saying by the Interfax news agency.
</P>
