<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Four Killed, 11 Wounded in Arkansas School Shooting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 24 (Xinhua) -- At least four people were
killed and 11 others wounded when two boys in camouflage ambushed
a group of middle school students in Arkansas Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Two suspects, ages 11 and 13, were taking into custody after
the 12:40 p.m. shooting outside Westside Middle School in
Jonesboro, Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
Among the wounded were two teachers and others were mostly
little girls.
</P>
<P>
The two boys were taken to the county jail. Two rifles and
other weapons were recovered.
</P>
<P>
The school has about 250 students in sixth and seventh grades.
It was unclear whether the suspects were students at the school.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that U.S. President Bill Clinton, who was on
his six-nation tour in Africa, said that he was "shocked and
heartbroken" by the deadly shooting.
</P>
<P>
It was the fourth fatal shooting rampage in a school in the
past five months.
</P>
<P>
On December 1, a 14-year-old student opened fire on a student
prayer circle in a hallway at Heath High School in West Paducah,
Kentucky. Three students were killed and five others wounded.
</P>
<P>
On December 15, a 14-year-old boy was arrested after wounding
two students outside a school in Stamps, Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
Two months earlier, a 16-year-old Mississippi boy was accused
of killing his mother, then going to school and shooting nine
students. Two of them died, including the boy's ex-girlfriend.
</P>
</TEXT>
