<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kodak Will Set up JV for Photo Materials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Approved by the State Council, a
joint venture to make photo materials will be established in east
China, today's "China Daily" reported.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing-based English newspaper said that the project will
involve over one billion US dollars from Eastman Kodak, one of the
biggest investments by a US company.
</P>
<P>
Under the deal, Kodak will form two new companies with Chinese
partners to make and market colour film, medical and industrial
X-ray film and other products in China and elsewhere in Asia.
Kodak already makes cameras, components and other products in
China.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese companies in the ventures are Shantou Era Photo
Materials in Guangdong Province and Xiamen Fuda Photo Materials in
Fujian Province, both of which make color film and paper; and Wuxi
Aermei Film and Chemical Corp of Jiangsu Province, which makes
medical and industrial X-ray film.
</P>
<P>
According to a market survey jointly done by the China
Enterprise Management Association, the China Enterprise
Association and the State Enterprise Information Exchange Center,
the sale of Kodak film, which ranked second to Fuji in China in
1996, jumped to first place last year with about a 39 percent
market share in China.
</P>
<P>
Kodak earned five million US dollars last year on sales of 14.7
billion US dollars after taking a 1.5 billion US dollars
restructuring charge and setting plans to cut 20,000 jobs, the
paper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
