<DOCNO> XIE19980325.0338 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Growth Reduced by Asian Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Latin American economists are
considering the effects of the wake of Asian financial crisis in
forecasting a regional economic growth of five percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Carlos Moneta, permanent secretary of the Latin-American
Economic System, made the point on Tuesday. He said the growth
rate last January was estimated at merely 3.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Chile, Peru, Brazil and Argentina, with an 80 percent share of
the region's trade with Asian countries, are the four suffering
most from the crisis, Moneta said.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, Latin America was better prepared than before
to face such a crisis, as could be seen in Brazil's case which
was starting to show recovery signs.
</P>
<P>
As for the International Monetary Fund (IMF), Moneta criticized
the organization for trying to apply the same solution to all
Asian-Pacific countries hit by the crisis by pressing them to open
their markets to the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
