<DOCNO> XIE19980325.0341 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Women and Children's Rights Well Protected in Tibet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, March 25 (Xinhua) -- In recent years, governments at all
levels in Tibet Autonomous Region have attached great importance
to the development of women and children affairs.
</P>
<P>
A number of local laws and regulations to protect the rights of
women and children have been issued by the regional government,
while all the 65 county-level administrative areas have set up
their own coordinative body on the issue.
</P>
<P>
The autonomous region has sent 22 local county magistrates to
attend national training programs on implementing national
policies on protecting women and children.
</P>
<P>
To better understand the situation in Tibet, two regional
government departments have jointly worked out a supervisional
system on the conditions of local children. Four government
reports on the issue have been completed and handed over to
related international bodies.
</P>
<P>
Since 1993, Tibet has invested 10.14 million yuan, including
1.22 million yuan from the Unicef, in the construction of women
and children's centers in five cities and prefectures.
</P>
<P>
The regional government has tried hard to help more local women
become government staff workers. A five-year plan (1996-2000) has
been worked out for the purpose.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year, women officials had accounted for 31
percent of the total in the autonomous region, 6.28 percentage
points over that of 1993. Meanwhile, women made up 10.94 percent
of the total number of regional leaders in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
In addition, efforts are being been made to protect legal
rights of women and children. Project Hope, a national
non-government program to help students from poor families, has
also benefited Tibetan children as more than 10,000 local school
drop-outs have returned to school.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
