<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cohen Says U.S.-Russia Military Ties on Track </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 24 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Defense Secretary of
State William Cohen said Tuesday that the reshuffle of the Russian
cabinet by President Boris Yeltsin will not slow the improvement
in military ties between Washington and Moscow.
</P>
<P>
During a photo opportunity with Georgian Defense Minister
Vardiko Nadibaidze, Cohen told reporters he had information
Yeltsin planned to keep Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev, Foreign
Minister Yevgeny Primakov and senior adviser Andrei Kokoshin in
their jobs.
</P>
<P>
"My information is that Minister Sergeyev along with Primakov
and Andrei Kokoshin, a principal adviser to President Yeltsin,
will remain in office," he said.
</P>
<P>
"So I do not anticipate it will have an impact on our
relationship. And I don't think it will have any bearing on the
ratification of START-2" strategic arms reduction treaty by the
Russian Duma, Cohen added.
</P>
<P>
He would not say where his information had come from, but
stressed that Monday's sacking was, as Yeltsin said, aimed at
boosting flagging economic reforms in Russia.
</P>
<P>
Cohen and Nadibaidze signed a defense cooperation agreement
between the U.S. and Georgia, under which the U.S. would provide
1.35 million U.S. dollars in foreign military financing to Georgia
this year.
</P>
<P>
Cohen said Georgia, an active participant in NATO's
"Partnership for Peace" (PFP) military cooperation program with
former communist states, would use the funds to buy military
radios for an infantry company that will take part in PFP
exercises.
</P>
<P>
Nadibaidze told reporters his ministry also believed Yeltsin
intended to keep Sergeyev and Kokoshin on the job in the Russian
cabinet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
