<DOCNO> XIE19980325.0365 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Mission in Congo Finds Bodies Removed From </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 24 (Xinhua) -- A U.N. mission
investigating alleged massacres in the former Zaire found that at
least one mass grave with all the bodies has been removed in a
possible attempt to destroy evidence, U.N. spokesman Juan Carlos
Brandt said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The team of U.N. experts were investigating reported massacres
of Rwandan Hutu refugees in the Democratic Republic of the Congo.
</P>
<P>
"Preliminary exploration of the site on March 18 by the experts
confirmed the existence of at least one mass grave, whose contents
appeared to have been removed several months after burial,
possible in an attempt to destroy evidence," Carlos told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
The location was near the scene where witnesses said Hutu
refugees were executed in May last year as now President Laurent
Kabila was about to seize power from the late Mobutu Sese Seko.
Kabila's forces and Rwandan Tutsi allies are suspected of killing
thousands of Hutu refugees during a bush war across the former
Zaire. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980325.0366 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Offers Indonesia With Aid to Combat Drought </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 24 (Xinhua) -- The State Department announced
Tuesday that Washington would offer 56 million dollars in food and
medical supplies to assist Indonesia which is suffering from the
worst drought in 50 years and a financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Undersecretary of State Stuart Eizenstat said the food and
medical aid was in addition to more than 520 million dollars in
assistance from programs of the U.S. Agency for International
Development and the Agriculture Department.
</P>
<P>
He said Indonesia has had difficulty importing food and other
necessities because letters of credit are not being readily
accepted by banks.
</P>
<P>
"Higher prices combined with lower incomes caused by the
economic downturn will make food and other essential goods
increasingly unaffordable by the poor," Eizenstat told a press
conference.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank will hold a meeting on April 1 in Washington to
assess Indonesia's humanitarian needs, he said.
</P>
<P>
"What we really want is to get an assessment of needs, and once
that assessment is done, then we can make an assessment of where
those resources will come from," he said.
</P>
<P>
Eizenstat said the humanitarian aid would not be linked to how
well Indonesia implemented strict economic reforms tied to the IMF
package.
</P>
<P>
"We have really tried to separate IMF conditionality from this
humanitarian package," he said.
</P>
<P>
Eizenstat said U.S. national interests in Indonesia were too
"significant" for Washington not to act when it is facing natural
disaster.
</P>
<P>
He said the United States had a vested interest in propping up
the "moderate" Muslim government that served as a voice of reason
in Asia and preserving access to ports where American warships can
undergo depot maintenance, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
