<DOCNO> XIE19980325.0368 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. House Panel Approves Bill for Paying U.N., IMF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 24 (Xinhua) -- A key U.S. House panel
approved a bill Tuesday that would provide 17.9 billion U.S.
dollars for the International Monetary Fund and 505 million U.S.
dollars to pay back dues to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The House Appropriations Committee approved the legislation by
voice vote. However, Democrats said the measure was insufficient
and predicted a confrontation.
</P>
<P>
The panel voted 30-25 to reject a Democratic amendment that
would have provided the full 926 million U.S. dollars for the
U.N. that President Bill Clinton seeks.
</P>
<P>
It also voted 29-25 to kill another Democratic amendment that
would have added protections for workers and the environment to a
list of restrictions legislators want to add to the IMF funds.
</P>
<P>
The panel's chairman, Rep. Bob Livingston, R-La., defended the
legislation and said the GOP conditions on the IMF funds were
responsible.
</P>
<P>
The conditions require the Clinton administration to
aggressively prod the IMF to tighten its lending policies.
</P>
<P>
The Senate, moving toward a final vote on a spending bill by
Wednesday, faced proposed amendments that included reducing the
U.S. contribution to NATO and urging allies to pay more for troop
deployments in the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Republican Senate leaders were close to an agreement
with the Clinton administration to use the spending bill to obtain
quick Senate approval of the administration's request for 18
billion U.S. dollars for the IMF.
</P>
<P>
The Senate is attempting to attach conditions on how the IMF
loans money, mainly to make sure that the loans are not used to
subsidize products made by countries that are economic rivals.
</P>
<P>
The administration had opposed the conditions. But, in hopes of
getting quicker action on the package, Treasury Secretary Robert
Rubin has been negotiating with Senate Republicans to make the
conditions less rigid. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
