<DOCNO> XIE19980325.0370 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Protest Upsets Denver Race Discussion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 24 (Xinhua) -- The advisory board for U.S.
President Bill Clinton's Initiative on Race Tuesday expressed the
hope that the rest of a three-day discussion in Denver, Colorado,
goes more smoothly than the raucous opening.
</P>
<P>
Protesters in the audience of more than 700 shouted Monday
night as Energy Secretary Federico Pena and other discussion
leaders tried to talk about racial stereotyping.
</P>
<P>
United Press International quoted Initiative spokeswoman Lydia
Sermons as saying, "We know that discussing issues about race can
be emotional and passionate exchanges," conceding that the protest
was "probably the most disruptive" of all the forums so far.
</P>
<P>
No changes in the formats of future meetings are planned,
Sermons said, including a panel discussion and a high school town
hall meeting on the Denver theme of stereotypes.
</P>
<P>
About 15 minutes into Monday night's event, American Indian
Movement activist Glenn Morris and about 25 protesters waved signs
and shouted complaints that the board did not include a Native
American member.
</P>
<P>
Actor James Edward Olmos was able to restore some order to the
meeting but other speakers were drowned out when they tried to
address the crowd and simply gave up.
</P>
<P>
Sermons said the board chose Denver as a meeting site to learn
how the community dealt with a series of hate crimes last fall,
including the racially-motivated slaying of a West African
refugee. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
